WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.169 --> 00:00:03.671
( pounding drums )

2
00:00:03.712 --> 00:00:05.965
( ethereal chorus )

3
00:00:06.005 --> 00:00:07.716
( drum phrase repeats )

4
00:00:10.051 --> 00:00:14.181
( woman vocalizing )

5
00:00:14.222 --> 00:00:16.141
( drums return )

6
00:00:24.149 --> 00:00:27.152
♪ ♪

7
00:00:48.173 --> 00:00:50.175
♪ ♪

8
00:01:10.153 --> 00:01:12.155
♪ ♪

9
00:01:33.552 --> 00:01:38.891
ODYSSEUS:
Men are haunted
by the vastness of eternity.

10
00:01:38.933 --> 00:01:40.935
And so we ask ourselves,

11
00:01:40.976 --> 00:01:45.064
will our actions echo
across the centuries?

12
00:01:45.146 --> 00:01:50.694
Will strangers hear our names
long after we're gone

13
00:01:50.736 --> 00:01:53.030
and wonder who we were,

14
00:01:53.072 --> 00:01:56.199
how bravely we fought,

15
00:01:56.241 --> 00:01:58.827
how fiercely we loved?

16
00:02:20.808 --> 00:02:25.145
( hoofbeats pounding )

17
00:02:30.567 --> 00:02:32.778
( horse neighing )

18
00:02:43.163 --> 00:02:46.165
♪ ♪

19
00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:53.757
( man shouting command )

20
00:02:58.595 --> 00:03:01.765
( man shouting )

21
00:03:08.939 --> 00:03:10.983
( man shouting )

22
00:03:21.994 --> 00:03:24.830
♪ ♪

23
00:03:24.872 --> 00:03:27.499
( whickering )

24
00:03:36.758 --> 00:03:38.844
( horse sputtering )

25
00:03:44.265 --> 00:03:45.767
( crows cawing )

26
00:03:49.146 --> 00:03:50.564
Good day for the crows.

27
00:03:50.605 --> 00:03:53.984
Remove your army
from my land.

28
00:03:54.026 --> 00:03:55.610
I like your land.

29
00:03:55.652 --> 00:03:57.738
I think we'll stay.

30
00:03:57.779 --> 00:03:59.698
I like your soldiers, too.

31
00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:01.533
They won't
fight for you.

32
00:04:01.575 --> 00:04:02.993
That's what the Messenians said.

33
00:04:03.035 --> 00:04:04.745
And the Arcadians.

34
00:04:04.786 --> 00:04:06.747
And the Epeians.

35
00:04:06.788 --> 00:04:08.498
Now...

36
00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:10.042
they all fight for me.

37
00:04:10.084 --> 00:04:11.960
You can't have the whole
world, Agamemnon.

38
00:04:12.002 --> 00:04:13.170
( laughs )

39
00:04:13.212 --> 00:04:14.922
It's too big,
even for you.

40
00:04:14.963 --> 00:04:18.008
I don't want to watch
another massacre.

41
00:04:18.050 --> 00:04:20.343
Let's settle this war
in the old manner.

42
00:04:20.385 --> 00:04:22.429
Your best fighter
against my best.

43
00:04:25.432 --> 00:04:27.684
And if my man wins?

44
00:04:27.726 --> 00:04:29.811
We'll leave Thessaly for good.

45
00:04:29.853 --> 00:04:33.398
( shouting ):
Boagrius!

46
00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:35.442
( men cheering )

47
00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:47.412
( cheering continues )

48
00:04:52.167 --> 00:04:53.752
( shouting ):
Achilles!

49
00:05:00.759 --> 00:05:03.095
( laughter )

50
00:05:03.137 --> 00:05:07.099
Boagrius has this effect
on many heroes.

51
00:05:07.141 --> 00:05:09.392
Careful who you insult,
old king.

52
00:05:12.187 --> 00:05:13.438
My King?

53
00:05:14.314 --> 00:05:15.607
Achilles is not with the army.

54
00:05:15.649 --> 00:05:16.650
Where is he?!

55
00:05:16.691 --> 00:05:18.485
I sent a boy to look for him.

56
00:05:21.155 --> 00:05:23.157
( dog barks )

57
00:05:43.135 --> 00:05:44.845
( gasps )

58
00:05:44.886 --> 00:05:47.472
I was having
a good dream.

59
00:05:49.641 --> 00:05:51.685
A very good dream.

60
00:05:51.726 --> 00:05:54.188
King Agamemnon sent me.

61
00:05:54.229 --> 00:05:55.814
He needs to dis...

62
00:05:55.856 --> 00:05:57.356
I'll speak to your 
king in the morning.

63
00:05:57.398 --> 00:05:58.525
But, my lord,

64
00:05:58.566 --> 00:06:00.068
it is morning.

65
00:06:03.113 --> 00:06:04.447
They're waiting for you.

66
00:06:04.489 --> 00:06:07.492
( exhales )

67
00:06:08.994 --> 00:06:11.913
( grunts )

68
00:06:11.955 --> 00:06:15.458
Are the stories
about you true?

69
00:06:16.877 --> 00:06:19.338
They say your mother
is an immortal goddess.

70
00:06:20.964 --> 00:06:22.132
They say you

71
00:06:22.174 --> 00:06:23.342
can't be killed.

72
00:06:23.382 --> 00:06:24.634
I wouldn't be bothering

73
00:06:24.676 --> 00:06:26.345
with the shield then, would I?

74
00:06:26.385 --> 00:06:28.847
The Thessalonian
you're fighting--

75
00:06:28.889 --> 00:06:31.308
he's the biggest man
I've ever seen.

76
00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:33.310
I wouldn't want to fight him.

77
00:06:35.354 --> 00:06:37.480
That's why
no one will remember your name.

78
00:06:43.486 --> 00:06:45.155
( men cheering )

79
00:06:45.197 --> 00:06:47.657
MEN ( chanting ):
Achilles! Achilles! Achilles!

80
00:06:47.699 --> 00:06:51.161
Achilles! Achilles! Achilles!

81
00:06:51.203 --> 00:06:53.205
Achilles! Achilles!

82
00:06:53.247 --> 00:06:56.415
Achilles! Achilles! Achilles...!

83
00:07:00.754 --> 00:07:02.797
( grunts ):
Hmm.

84
00:07:02.839 --> 00:07:04.465
Perhaps we should
have our war tomorrow

85
00:07:04.507 --> 00:07:06.176
when you're
better rested.

86
00:07:06.218 --> 00:07:07.426
I should have you whipped

87
00:07:07.468 --> 00:07:09.263
for your impudence.

88
00:07:11.223 --> 00:07:13.141
Perhaps you
should fight him.

89
00:07:13.183 --> 00:07:15.227
Achilles.

90
00:07:15.269 --> 00:07:17.271
Achilles?

91
00:07:19.273 --> 00:07:21.233
Look at the men's faces.

92
00:07:21.275 --> 00:07:23.318
You can save hundreds of them.

93
00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:27.239
You can end this war
with a swing of your sword.

94
00:07:27.281 --> 00:07:29.241
Let them go home
to their wives.

95
00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.874
Imagine a king
who fights his own battles.

96
00:07:37.916 --> 00:07:40.043
Wouldn't that be a sight?

97
00:07:43.088 --> 00:07:45.715
Of all the warlords
loved by the gods,

98
00:07:45.757 --> 00:07:48.843
I hate him the most.

99
00:07:50.971 --> 00:07:52.513
( yelling )

100
00:07:52.555 --> 00:07:57.185
( men cheering )

101
00:07:57.227 --> 00:07:58.770
( yelling )

102
00:07:58.812 --> 00:08:00.521
( grunts )

103
00:08:03.942 --> 00:08:05.193
( grunts )

104
00:08:07.612 --> 00:08:08.822
( loud groan )

105
00:08:11.658 --> 00:08:14.161
( grunts )

106
00:08:15.245 --> 00:08:16.871
( breathing rapidly )

107
00:08:23.086 --> 00:08:24.587
( groans )

108
00:08:24.629 --> 00:08:25.755
( grunts )

109
00:08:27.757 --> 00:08:30.051
( men cheering and yelling )

110
00:08:32.137 --> 00:08:34.139
MEN ( chanting ):
Achilles! Achilles!

111
00:08:34.181 --> 00:08:36.724
Achilles! Achilles...!

112
00:08:40.812 --> 00:08:42.981
Is there no one else?

113
00:08:47.944 --> 00:08:51.656
Is there no one else?!

114
00:08:54.868 --> 00:08:56.870
Who are you,
soldier?

115
00:08:56.911 --> 00:08:59.373
Achilles.

116
00:08:59.414 --> 00:09:01.375
Son of Peleus.

117
00:09:01.416 --> 00:09:03.751
Achilles?

118
00:09:03.793 --> 00:09:06.463
I'll remember the name.

119
00:09:06.505 --> 00:09:10.258
The ruler of Thessaly
carries this scepter.

120
00:09:10.300 --> 00:09:13.345
Give it to
your king.

121
00:09:14.888 --> 00:09:16.890
He's not my king.

122
00:09:21.061 --> 00:09:23.146
( indistinct shouts
and chatter )

123
00:09:29.361 --> 00:09:30.611
MEN:
Brothers in arms!

124
00:09:30.653 --> 00:09:31.821
MAN:
Friendship!

125
00:09:31.863 --> 00:09:33.198
MEN:
Friendship!

126
00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:35.325
( men cheering )

127
00:09:35.367 --> 00:09:36.368
MAN:
Brothers in arms!

128
00:09:36.410 --> 00:09:37.660
MEN:
Brothers in arms!

129
00:09:37.702 --> 00:09:39.329
MAN:
Friendship!

130
00:09:39.371 --> 00:09:40.914
MEN:
Friendship!

131
00:09:40.955 --> 00:09:43.166
( men cheering )

132
00:09:43.208 --> 00:09:45.335
( indistinct chatter )

133
00:09:45.377 --> 00:09:47.795
( banging on table )

134
00:09:47.837 --> 00:09:49.797
Princes of Troy,

135
00:09:49.839 --> 00:09:51.508
on our last night together,

136
00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:54.094
Queen Helen
and I salute you.

137
00:09:54.135 --> 00:09:56.804
( men cheering,
staffs banging on floor )

138
00:09:56.846 --> 00:09:59.182
We've had our conflicts before,
it's true.

139
00:09:59.224 --> 00:10:01.476
We fought many battles,
Sparta and Troy.

140
00:10:01.518 --> 00:10:02.519
And fought well!

141
00:10:02.561 --> 00:10:04.521
( cheering )

142
00:10:04.563 --> 00:10:06.147
But I have always respected

143
00:10:06.189 --> 00:10:07.315
your father.

144
00:10:07.357 --> 00:10:09.484
Priam is a good king,
a good man.

145
00:10:09.526 --> 00:10:11.486
I respected him
as an adversary,

146
00:10:11.528 --> 00:10:12.695
I respect him

147
00:10:12.737 --> 00:10:14.030
now as my ally.

148
00:10:14.072 --> 00:10:15.198
( cheering )

149
00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.700
Hector, Paris, young princes.

150
00:10:17.742 --> 00:10:19.077
Come, stand.

151
00:10:19.119 --> 00:10:21.246
Drink with me.

152
00:10:23.457 --> 00:10:24.874
Let us drink to peace.

153
00:10:24.916 --> 00:10:26.960
To peace.

154
00:10:27.001 --> 00:10:29.379
Between Troy and Sparta.

155
00:10:29.421 --> 00:10:30.797
( cheering )

156
00:10:30.838 --> 00:10:32.424
May the gods keep the wolves
in the hills

157
00:10:32.466 --> 00:10:33.883
and the women in our beds.

158
00:10:33.925 --> 00:10:35.510
( cheering )

159
00:10:39.097 --> 00:10:41.849
( lively music plays )

160
00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:55.238
( laughs )

161
00:10:55.280 --> 00:10:56.406
( laughs )

162
00:10:56.448 --> 00:11:00.285
( laughs )

163
00:11:00.327 --> 00:11:01.119
For the gods.

164
00:11:01.161 --> 00:11:02.662
For the gods.

165
00:11:02.703 --> 00:11:05.332
( laughter )

166
00:11:05.373 --> 00:11:07.708
( indistinct chatter )

167
00:11:09.127 --> 00:11:11.296
MAN:
Carry on.

168
00:11:30.106 --> 00:11:32.150
( jewelry clattering )

169
00:11:37.696 --> 00:11:39.698
( door creaking )

170
00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:47.332
You shouldn't be here.

171
00:11:47.374 --> 00:11:49.584
That's what you said last night.

172
00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:53.838
Last night was a mistake.

173
00:11:56.049 --> 00:11:59.052
And the night
before?

174
00:11:59.093 --> 00:12:01.471
I've made many mistakes
this week.

175
00:12:09.854 --> 00:12:11.898
( sighs )

176
00:12:15.818 --> 00:12:17.445
Do you want me to go?

177
00:12:26.621 --> 00:12:28.623
( sighs )

178
00:12:40.801 --> 00:12:42.970
( cheering )

179
00:12:45.056 --> 00:12:47.517
( low and indistinct chatter )

180
00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:50.144
( men singing )

181
00:12:56.234 --> 00:12:59.237
( chuckles and groans )

182
00:13:01.197 --> 00:13:04.451
Pearls
from the Sea of Propontis.

183
00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:14.252
They're beautiful.

184
00:13:16.254 --> 00:13:18.923
But I can't wear them.

185
00:13:18.965 --> 00:13:20.592
Menelaus would kill us both.

186
00:13:20.634 --> 00:13:23.052
( soft gasp )

187
00:13:23.094 --> 00:13:26.222
Don't be
afraid of him.

188
00:13:26.264 --> 00:13:28.308
I'm not afraid of dying.

189
00:13:31.185 --> 00:13:33.313
I'm afraid of tomorrow.

190
00:13:36.608 --> 00:13:38.568
I-I'm afraid
of watching you sail away

191
00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:40.695
and knowing
you'll never come back.

192
00:13:44.949 --> 00:13:46.451
( sniffs )

193
00:13:46.493 --> 00:13:49.996
Before you came to Sparta,
I was a ghost.

194
00:13:50.037 --> 00:13:54.751
I walked, and I ate,
and I swam in the sea...

195
00:13:54.793 --> 00:13:56.877
but I was just a ghost.

196
00:13:56.919 --> 00:13:59.880
You don't have
to fear tomorrow.

197
00:13:59.922 --> 00:14:02.258
Come with me.

198
00:14:06.554 --> 00:14:08.264
Don't play with me.

199
00:14:08.306 --> 00:14:10.517
Don't play.

200
00:14:10.558 --> 00:14:13.936
If you come, we'll
never be safe.

201
00:14:13.978 --> 00:14:15.229
Men will hunt us,

202
00:14:15.271 --> 00:14:19.025
the gods will curse us.

203
00:14:19.066 --> 00:14:20.568
But I'll love you.

204
00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:22.570
( soft gasp )

205
00:14:22.612 --> 00:14:24.864
Till the day
they burn my body,

206
00:14:24.905 --> 00:14:28.284
I will love you.

207
00:14:37.544 --> 00:14:40.046
♪ ♪

208
00:14:49.514 --> 00:14:51.558
A beautiful morning.

209
00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:53.893
Poseidon has blessed our voyage.

210
00:14:53.934 --> 00:14:56.145
Sometimes the gods
bless you in the morning

211
00:14:56.187 --> 00:14:57.856
and curse you
in the afternoon.

212
00:14:57.938 --> 00:15:00.400
MAN:
Drop sail!

213
00:15:02.736 --> 00:15:04.987
Do you love me, brother?

214
00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:08.157
Would you protect me
against any enemy?

215
00:15:10.744 --> 00:15:12.746
The last time you
spoke to me like this,

216
00:15:12.787 --> 00:15:14.121
you were ten years old,

217
00:15:14.163 --> 00:15:17.250
and you'd just stolen
father's horse.

218
00:15:17.291 --> 00:15:19.252
What have you done now?

219
00:15:20.795 --> 00:15:22.672
I must show you something.

220
00:15:32.181 --> 00:15:34.225
♪ ♪

221
00:15:47.906 --> 00:15:48.656
( gasps )

222
00:15:52.201 --> 00:15:54.829
( gasps )
Where is she?

223
00:15:54.871 --> 00:15:56.372
I swear by the
father of the gods,

224
00:15:56.414 --> 00:15:59.125
I will gut you here
if you don't tell me!

225
00:15:59.166 --> 00:16:01.210
MAN:
My King!

226
00:16:02.211 --> 00:16:03.755
She left.

227
00:16:03.797 --> 00:16:05.172
With the Trojans.

228
00:16:06.215 --> 00:16:08.384
The fisherman here

229
00:16:08.426 --> 00:16:10.094
saw her board their ship.

230
00:16:10.136 --> 00:16:12.430
The Trojans?

231
00:16:14.432 --> 00:16:17.894
With the young
prince, Paris. She....

232
00:16:17.936 --> 00:16:21.021
Get my ship ready.

233
00:16:22.148 --> 00:16:24.191
Turn us 'round.
Back to Sparta.

234
00:16:24.233 --> 00:16:25.693
Higher on the sail!

235
00:16:25.735 --> 00:16:26.694
Wait, wait.

236
00:16:26.736 --> 00:16:27.695
You fool.

237
00:16:27.737 --> 00:16:28.696
Listen to me--

238
00:16:28.738 --> 00:16:30.239
Do you know what you've done?!

239
00:16:30.281 --> 00:16:32.867
Do you know how many years
our father worked for peace?

240
00:16:34.034 --> 00:16:34.994
I love her.

241
00:16:35.035 --> 00:16:36.162
( groans )

242
00:16:36.203 --> 00:16:39.290
It's all a game to you,
isn't it?

243
00:16:39.332 --> 00:16:40.750
You roam from town to town

244
00:16:40.792 --> 00:16:42.669
bedding merchant's wives
and temple mates.

245
00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:45.421
And you think you know
something about love.

246
00:16:45.463 --> 00:16:47.173
What about your father's love?

247
00:16:47.214 --> 00:16:50.009
You spat on him when you
brought her on this ship!

248
00:16:50.050 --> 00:16:52.094
What about the love
for your country?

249
00:16:52.136 --> 00:16:54.054
You'd let Troy burn
for this woman?

250
00:16:56.307 --> 00:16:57.767
( pants )

251
00:16:57.809 --> 00:17:00.102
I won't let you
start a war for her.

252
00:17:00.144 --> 00:17:01.479
May I speak?

253
00:17:02.939 --> 00:17:04.440
What you say is true.

254
00:17:04.482 --> 00:17:06.985
I've wronged you,
I've wronged our father.

255
00:17:07.026 --> 00:17:09.779
If you want to take Helen
back to Sparta, so be it.

256
00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:12.699
But I go with her.

257
00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:15.284
To Sparta?
They'll kill you.

258
00:17:15.326 --> 00:17:16.661
Then I'll die fighting.

259
00:17:16.703 --> 00:17:20.122
Oh, and that sounds heroic
to you, doesn't it?

260
00:17:20.164 --> 00:17:21.624
To die fighting?

261
00:17:21.666 --> 00:17:23.626
Tell me, little brother,
have you ever killed a man?

262
00:17:23.668 --> 00:17:24.585
No.

263
00:17:24.627 --> 00:17:25.795
Ever seen a man die in combat?

264
00:17:25.837 --> 00:17:26.713
No.

265
00:17:26.754 --> 00:17:28.339
I've killed men,

266
00:17:28.381 --> 00:17:30.257
and I've heard them dying,

267
00:17:30.299 --> 00:17:31.467
and I've watched them dying,

268
00:17:31.509 --> 00:17:33.177
and there's nothing
glorious about it.

269
00:17:33.219 --> 00:17:34.345
Nothing poetic.

270
00:17:34.387 --> 00:17:35.972
You say you want
to die for love,

271
00:17:36.014 --> 00:17:37.557
but you know nothing
about dying,

272
00:17:37.598 --> 00:17:39.934
and you know nothing
about love!

273
00:17:39.976 --> 00:17:41.019
All the same...

274
00:17:41.059 --> 00:17:43.145
I go with her.

275
00:17:43.187 --> 00:17:45.398
I won't ask you
to fight my war.

276
00:17:48.526 --> 00:17:50.194
You already have.

277
00:17:52.446 --> 00:17:53.489
To Troy!

278
00:17:53.531 --> 00:17:54.908
About ship!

279
00:17:54.949 --> 00:17:55.992
Set sail!

280
00:18:03.875 --> 00:18:07.837
( indistinct chatter )

281
00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:12.967
( doors creak and thud )

282
00:18:31.652 --> 00:18:32.820
I want her back.

283
00:18:32.862 --> 00:18:35.114
Well, of course you do.

284
00:18:35.155 --> 00:18:37.157
She's a beautiful woman.

285
00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:40.870
I want her back so I can kill
her with my own two hands.

286
00:18:40.912 --> 00:18:44.457
And I won't rest till I've
burned Troy to the ground.

287
00:18:44.498 --> 00:18:46.709
I thought you wanted
peace with Troy.

288
00:18:46.751 --> 00:18:49.462
I should have listened to you.

289
00:18:49.503 --> 00:18:51.422
Peace is for the women...

290
00:18:51.464 --> 00:18:53.716
and the weak.

291
00:18:53.758 --> 00:18:57.971
Empires are forged by war.

292
00:18:58.012 --> 00:19:01.766
All my life I've stood by your
side, fought your enemies.

293
00:19:01.808 --> 00:19:04.060
You're the elder,
you reap the glory.

294
00:19:04.102 --> 00:19:05.937
This is the way of the world.

295
00:19:05.979 --> 00:19:07.897
But have I ever complained,
brother?

296
00:19:07.939 --> 00:19:09.857
Have I ever asked you
for anything?

297
00:19:09.899 --> 00:19:11.191
Never.

298
00:19:11.233 --> 00:19:13.319
You're a man of honor.

299
00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:16.656
Will you go to war with me,
brother?

300
00:19:27.165 --> 00:19:31.253
AGAMEMNON:
I always thought my brother's
wife was a foolish woman,

301
00:19:31.295 --> 00:19:33.756
but she's proved
to be very useful.

302
00:19:33.798 --> 00:19:35.133
( chuckles )

303
00:19:35.173 --> 00:19:37.010
The Trojans have never been
conquered.

304
00:19:37.051 --> 00:19:39.303
Some say they can't
be conquered.

305
00:19:39.345 --> 00:19:41.931
Old King Priam
thinks he's untouchable

306
00:19:41.973 --> 00:19:44.058
behind his high walls.

307
00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:47.436
He thinks the sun god
will protect him.

308
00:19:47.478 --> 00:19:50.272
But the gods protect only...

309
00:19:50.773 --> 00:19:52.232
the strong!

310
00:19:53.609 --> 00:19:56.070
If Troy falls...

311
00:19:56.112 --> 00:19:57.947
I control...

312
00:19:57.989 --> 00:19:59.281
the Aegean.

313
00:19:59.323 --> 00:20:02.326
Hector commands
the finest army in the east.

314
00:20:02.368 --> 00:20:03.828
I'll attack them

315
00:20:03.870 --> 00:20:05.454
with the greatest force
the world has ever seen.

316
00:20:05.496 --> 00:20:09.458
I want all the Kings of Greece
and their armies.

317
00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:11.293
Send emissaries in the morning.

318
00:20:11.335 --> 00:20:13.171
One last thing.

319
00:20:13.211 --> 00:20:17.133
We need Achilles
and his Myrmidons.

320
00:20:18.592 --> 00:20:20.636
( whispering ):
Achilles.

321
00:20:21.637 --> 00:20:24.057
He can't be controlled.

322
00:20:24.098 --> 00:20:26.142
He's as likely to fight us
as the Trojans.

323
00:20:26.184 --> 00:20:29.812
We don't need to control him,
we need to unleash him.

324
00:20:29.854 --> 00:20:32.982
That man was born to end lives.

325
00:20:33.024 --> 00:20:34.984
Yes, he's a gifted killer.

326
00:20:35.026 --> 00:20:37.444
But he threatens
everything I've built.

327
00:20:37.486 --> 00:20:39.822
Before me, Greece was nothing.

328
00:20:39.864 --> 00:20:42.158
I brought
all the Greek kingdoms together.

329
00:20:42.200 --> 00:20:44.618
I created a nation
out of fire worshippers

330
00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:46.162
and snake eaters!

331
00:20:46.204 --> 00:20:49.123
I build the future, Nestor.
Me!

332
00:20:50.708 --> 00:20:53.169
Achilles is the past.

333
00:20:53.211 --> 00:20:55.504
A man who fights for no flag,

334
00:20:55.546 --> 00:20:57.924
a man loyal to no country.

335
00:20:57.965 --> 00:21:01.010
How many battles have we won
off the edge of his sword?

336
00:21:01.052 --> 00:21:05.014
This'll be the greatest war
the world has ever seen.

337
00:21:05.056 --> 00:21:07.558
We need the greatest warrior.

338
00:21:09.643 --> 00:21:11.269
( sighs )

339
00:21:11.311 --> 00:21:14.232
There's only one man
he'll listen to.

340
00:21:17.235 --> 00:21:20.238
( clack of wooden swords )

341
00:21:31.082 --> 00:21:31.874
Never hesitate.

342
00:21:33.333 --> 00:21:34.543
( grunts )

343
00:21:43.427 --> 00:21:44.262
Nervous?

344
00:21:47.598 --> 00:21:48.599
Petrified.

345
00:21:50.059 --> 00:21:51.269
( grunts )

346
00:21:51.309 --> 00:21:53.104
You told me never
to change sword hands.

347
00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:56.816
Yes. When you know
how to use it,

348
00:21:56.857 --> 00:21:58.358
you won't be
taking my orders.

349
00:22:07.868 --> 00:22:09.536
( men exclaim )

350
00:22:14.541 --> 00:22:16.002
( chuckles )

351
00:22:17.295 --> 00:22:18.587
Your reputation

352
00:22:18.629 --> 00:22:21.590
for hospitality
is fast becoming legend.

353
00:22:21.632 --> 00:22:23.759
( chuckles )

354
00:22:26.762 --> 00:22:29.307
Patroclus, my cousin.

355
00:22:29.347 --> 00:22:31.809
Odysseus, King of Ithaca.

356
00:22:31.851 --> 00:22:33.769
Patroclus.

357
00:22:33.811 --> 00:22:35.855
I knew your parents well.

358
00:22:35.896 --> 00:22:38.274
I miss them.

359
00:22:38.316 --> 00:22:41.652
Now you have this one
watching over you, eh?

360
00:22:41.694 --> 00:22:44.697
Learning from Achilles
himself.

361
00:22:44.738 --> 00:22:47.365
Kings would kill
for the honor.

362
00:22:47.407 --> 00:22:49.160
Are you here
at Agamemnon's bidding?

363
00:22:51.287 --> 00:22:52.538
We need to talk.

364
00:22:56.042 --> 00:22:58.002
I will not fight for him.

365
00:22:58.044 --> 00:23:00.671
I'm not asking you
to fight for him.

366
00:23:02.965 --> 00:23:04.466
I'm asking you
to fight for the Greeks.

367
00:23:04.508 --> 00:23:05.968
Why?

368
00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:07.385
Are the Greeks tired
of fighting each other?

369
00:23:07.427 --> 00:23:08.804
For now.

370
00:23:08.846 --> 00:23:11.140
The Trojans
never harmed me.

371
00:23:11.182 --> 00:23:13.184
They insulted Greece.

372
00:23:13.226 --> 00:23:14.560
They insulted one Greek,

373
00:23:14.601 --> 00:23:16.020
a man who couldn't
hold onto his wife.

374
00:23:16.062 --> 00:23:17.437
What business is that of mine?

375
00:23:17.479 --> 00:23:19.732
Your business is war,
my friend.

376
00:23:19.773 --> 00:23:21.483
Is it?

377
00:23:21.525 --> 00:23:22.693
The man has no honor.

378
00:23:22.735 --> 00:23:24.402
Let Achilles fight for honor.

379
00:23:24.444 --> 00:23:26.155
Let Agamemnon fight for power.

380
00:23:26.197 --> 00:23:28.824
And let the gods decide
which man to glorify.

381
00:23:28.866 --> 00:23:30.076
For the Greeks!

382
00:23:30.117 --> 00:23:33.787
Forget Agamemnon.
Fight for me.

383
00:23:33.829 --> 00:23:35.081
My wife will feel

384
00:23:35.122 --> 00:23:37.415
much better if she knows
you're by my side.

385
00:23:37.457 --> 00:23:39.001
I'll feel much better.

386
00:23:39.043 --> 00:23:40.544
( grunts )

387
00:23:40.586 --> 00:23:42.922
We're sending the largest fleet
that ever sailed.

388
00:23:42.963 --> 00:23:45.966
A thousand ships.

389
00:23:46.008 --> 00:23:47.676
PATROCLUS:
Prince Hector, is he

390
00:23:47.718 --> 00:23:48.969
as good a warrior
as they say?

391
00:23:49.011 --> 00:23:51.847
The best of all the Trojans.

392
00:23:51.889 --> 00:23:54.350
Some say he's better
than all the Greeks, too.

393
00:23:55.684 --> 00:23:57.686
Even if your cousin
doesn't come,

394
00:23:57.728 --> 00:23:59.688
I hope you'll join us,
Patroclus.

395
00:23:59.730 --> 00:24:01.399
We could use
a strong arm like yours.

396
00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.860
Play your tricks on me,
but not my cousin.

397
00:24:04.902 --> 00:24:08.530
You have your sword,
I have my tricks.

398
00:24:08.572 --> 00:24:11.491
We play with the toys
the gods give us.

399
00:24:13.119 --> 00:24:15.079
We sail for Troy in three days.

400
00:24:19.541 --> 00:24:21.585
This war will never be
forgotten.

401
00:24:21.627 --> 00:24:24.838
Nor will the heroes
who fight in it.

402
00:24:34.598 --> 00:24:36.809
♪ ♪

403
00:24:44.191 --> 00:24:47.278
( gentle splashing )

404
00:24:53.284 --> 00:24:56.203
I knew they would come for you.

405
00:24:56.245 --> 00:24:57.997
Long before you were born,

406
00:24:58.038 --> 00:25:01.083
I knew they
would come.

407
00:25:01.125 --> 00:25:04.628
They want you to fight in Troy.

408
00:25:10.176 --> 00:25:13.304
I'm making you
another seashell necklace.

409
00:25:13.346 --> 00:25:15.555
Like the ones I used to make you
when you were a boy.

410
00:25:15.597 --> 00:25:17.557
Do you remember?

411
00:25:20.311 --> 00:25:22.896
Mother...

412
00:25:25.732 --> 00:25:28.361
tonight I decide.

413
00:25:28.402 --> 00:25:30.863
If you stay in Larissa...

414
00:25:30.904 --> 00:25:32.490
you will find peace.

415
00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.950
You'll find a wonderful woman.

416
00:25:34.992 --> 00:25:36.785
You will have sons
and daughters,

417
00:25:36.827 --> 00:25:38.412
and they will have children.

418
00:25:38.454 --> 00:25:39.913
And they will love you.

419
00:25:39.955 --> 00:25:43.250
And when you are gone,
they will remember you.

420
00:25:46.837 --> 00:25:50.841
But when your children are dead,
and their children after them...

421
00:25:52.051 --> 00:25:54.261
your name will be lost.

422
00:25:57.848 --> 00:26:03.561
If you go to Troy,
glory will be yours.

423
00:26:03.603 --> 00:26:07.441
They will write stories
about your victories

424
00:26:07.483 --> 00:26:09.527
for thousands of years.

425
00:26:09.567 --> 00:26:12.946
The world
will remember your name.

426
00:26:12.988 --> 00:26:15.408
But if you go to Troy...

427
00:26:17.993 --> 00:26:21.080
you will never come home.

428
00:26:21.121 --> 00:26:27.503
For your glory walks
hand-in-hand with your doom.

429
00:26:27.545 --> 00:26:30.130
And I shall never
see you again.

430
00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:40.766
♪ ♪

431
00:26:48.857 --> 00:26:50.568
( men shouting )

432
00:26:59.326 --> 00:27:01.328
♪ ♪

433
00:27:18.762 --> 00:27:20.764
♪ ♪

434
00:27:29.189 --> 00:27:33.110
( crowd cheering )

435
00:27:50.877 --> 00:27:53.631
( cheering continues )

436
00:27:59.178 --> 00:28:01.805
♪ ♪

437
00:28:11.940 --> 00:28:14.610
( cheering )

438
00:28:22.075 --> 00:28:24.744
♪ ♪

439
00:28:37.675 --> 00:28:41.970
( applause )

440
00:28:48.935 --> 00:28:50.103
My son.

441
00:28:50.145 --> 00:28:51.855
Father.

442
00:28:57.069 --> 00:28:58.195
Paris.

443
00:29:04.451 --> 00:29:06.620
Father...

444
00:29:06.662 --> 00:29:08.664
this is Helen.

445
00:29:08.706 --> 00:29:11.417
Helen?

446
00:29:11.458 --> 00:29:12.418
Helen of Sparta?

447
00:29:12.459 --> 00:29:14.127
Helen of Troy.

448
00:29:16.963 --> 00:29:20.217
I've heard rumors
of your beauty.

449
00:29:22.302 --> 00:29:26.223
For once,
the gossips were right.

450
00:29:28.517 --> 00:29:29.809
Welcome.

451
00:29:29.851 --> 00:29:32.979
Come, you must be tired.

452
00:29:45.659 --> 00:29:46.826
Look.

453
00:29:46.868 --> 00:29:48.287
( gasps )

454
00:29:48.328 --> 00:29:51.206
He's grown.

455
00:29:51.248 --> 00:29:52.291
He's strong.

456
00:29:52.332 --> 00:29:53.959
PARIS:
Briseis!

457
00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:55.001
Paris!

458
00:29:58.338 --> 00:30:02.842
Beloved cousin, your beauty
grows with each new moon.

459
00:30:02.884 --> 00:30:05.178
Briseis.

460
00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.348
A servant of Apollo now.

461
00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:10.434
The young men of Troy
were devastated

462
00:30:10.476 --> 00:30:12.561
when Briseis chose
the virgin robes.

463
00:30:16.607 --> 00:30:18.858
♪ ♪

464
00:30:34.040 --> 00:30:38.545
HECTOR:
Father, I know this is
the last thing we need.

465
00:30:38.587 --> 00:30:40.964
It is the will of the gods.

466
00:30:41.006 --> 00:30:43.592
Everything is in their hands.

467
00:30:43.634 --> 00:30:46.470
But I'm surprised you
let him bring her.

468
00:30:46.512 --> 00:30:48.096
If I had let him
fight Menelaus for her,

469
00:30:48.138 --> 00:30:49.431
you'd be burning
your son's body

470
00:30:49.473 --> 00:30:50.724
instead of welcoming
a daughter.

471
00:30:50.766 --> 00:30:54.060
We could send
peace envoys to Menelaus.

472
00:30:54.102 --> 00:30:55.354
You know Menelaus.

473
00:30:55.395 --> 00:30:57.022
He'd spear their heads
to his gate.

474
00:30:57.063 --> 00:30:59.149
What would you have me do?

475
00:30:59.191 --> 00:31:02.861
Put her on a ship
and send her home.

476
00:31:05.864 --> 00:31:07.741
Women have always loved Paris,

477
00:31:07.783 --> 00:31:10.868
and he has loved them back,
but this is different.

478
00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:13.413
Something has changed in him.

479
00:31:13.455 --> 00:31:17.167
If we send her home to Menelaus,
he will follow her.

480
00:31:17.209 --> 00:31:21.129
This is my country,
and these are my countrymen.

481
00:31:21.171 --> 00:31:22.798
I don't want to see them suffer

482
00:31:22.840 --> 00:31:24.717
so my brother
can have his prize.

483
00:31:24.758 --> 00:31:27.845
And it's not just the
Spartans coming after her.

484
00:31:27.885 --> 00:31:30.514
By now, Menelaus
has gone to Agamemnon.

485
00:31:30.556 --> 00:31:33.141
And Agamemnon has wanted
to destroy us for years.

486
00:31:33.183 --> 00:31:36.520
Enemies have been attacking us
for centuries.

487
00:31:36.562 --> 00:31:38.271
Our walls still stand.

488
00:31:38.313 --> 00:31:42.317
Father, we can't win this war.

489
00:31:42.359 --> 00:31:45.571
Apollo watches over us.

490
00:31:45.612 --> 00:31:48.824
Even Agamemnon
is no match for the gods.

491
00:31:48.866 --> 00:31:51.744
And how many battalions
does the sun god command?

492
00:31:51.785 --> 00:31:53.495
Do not mock the gods.

493
00:31:58.751 --> 00:32:02.629
HELEN:
They're coming for me.

494
00:32:02.671 --> 00:32:04.506
The wind
is bringing them closer.

495
00:32:04.548 --> 00:32:06.258
What if we left?

496
00:32:06.299 --> 00:32:09.344
Tonight... right now.

497
00:32:09.386 --> 00:32:11.471
What if we went
down to the stables,

498
00:32:11.513 --> 00:32:13.014
took two horses and left?

499
00:32:13.056 --> 00:32:15.684
Ride east, keep riding.

500
00:32:15.726 --> 00:32:17.185
And go where?

501
00:32:17.227 --> 00:32:19.020
Away from here.

502
00:32:19.062 --> 00:32:22.691
I could hunt deer, rabbit.
I could feed us.

503
00:32:25.652 --> 00:32:27.028
But this is your home.

504
00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:29.364
You left your home for me.

505
00:32:33.410 --> 00:32:36.288
Sparta was never my home.

506
00:32:36.329 --> 00:32:39.249
My parents sent my there
when I was 16 to marry Menelaus.

507
00:32:39.291 --> 00:32:41.251
But it was never my home.

508
00:32:41.293 --> 00:32:43.169
We'll live
off the land.

509
00:32:43.211 --> 00:32:45.547
No more palaces for us.
No more servants.

510
00:32:45.589 --> 00:32:47.090
We don't need any of that.

511
00:32:47.132 --> 00:32:48.133
And your family?

512
00:32:48.174 --> 00:32:50.677
We'd be protecting my family.

513
00:32:50.719 --> 00:32:52.554
If we're not here,
what need is there for war?

514
00:32:52.596 --> 00:32:54.514
Menelaus won't give up.

515
00:32:54.556 --> 00:32:56.558
He'll track us
to the end of the world.

516
00:32:56.600 --> 00:32:58.226
He doesn't know these lands.
I do.

517
00:32:58.268 --> 00:33:00.270
We can lose
ourselves in a day.

518
00:33:00.312 --> 00:33:02.689
You don't know Menelaus.

519
00:33:02.731 --> 00:33:04.483
You don't know
his brother.

520
00:33:04.524 --> 00:33:08.236
They'll burn every house
in Troy to find us.

521
00:33:08.278 --> 00:33:11.740
They'll never believe
we've left.

522
00:33:11.782 --> 00:33:15.619
And even if they do,
they'll burn it for spite.

523
00:33:18.371 --> 00:33:22.000
Then I'll make it easy
for him to find me.

524
00:33:24.085 --> 00:33:26.922
I'll walk right up to him
and tell him you're mine.

525
00:33:31.844 --> 00:33:34.471
You're very young, my love.

526
00:33:34.513 --> 00:33:40.686
♪ ♪

527
00:33:59.496 --> 00:34:01.498
♪ ♪

528
00:34:06.670 --> 00:34:10.340
( shouts and chatter )

529
00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:22.811
( grunting )

530
00:34:25.104 --> 00:34:28.400
♪ ♪

531
00:34:39.160 --> 00:34:41.287
( chanting )

532
00:34:42.372 --> 00:34:45.042
Look at that.

533
00:34:45.083 --> 00:34:48.045
Hey?

534
00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:50.923
( coos )

535
00:34:54.968 --> 00:34:57.470
( gong rings )

536
00:34:57.512 --> 00:34:59.932
( distant yells )

537
00:35:01.641 --> 00:35:03.894
( gong rings )

538
00:35:07.397 --> 00:35:08.523
( gong rings )

539
00:35:08.565 --> 00:35:09.691
( baby cries )

540
00:35:29.753 --> 00:35:31.880
( myriad fearful voices )

541
00:35:39.387 --> 00:35:40.847
Take up your positions!

542
00:35:47.938 --> 00:35:51.316
♪ ♪

543
00:36:01.284 --> 00:36:03.536
( grunting )

544
00:36:09.334 --> 00:36:11.168
My lord?

545
00:36:11.210 --> 00:36:14.840
Should we wait
for the others?

546
00:36:14.881 --> 00:36:17.759
They brought us here
for war, didn't they?

547
00:36:17.801 --> 00:36:19.177
Yes, but Agamemnon's orders--

548
00:36:19.218 --> 00:36:21.054
You fight for me,
Eudorus, or Agamemnon?

549
00:36:21.096 --> 00:36:22.764
For you, my lord.

550
00:36:22.806 --> 00:36:24.891
Then fight for me,

551
00:36:24.933 --> 00:36:27.644
and let the servants
of Agamemnon fight for him.

552
00:36:31.564 --> 00:36:33.274
Black sail.

553
00:36:33.316 --> 00:36:34.359
It's Achilles.

554
00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:36.862
AGAMEMNON:
What's the fool doing?

555
00:36:36.903 --> 00:36:39.990
He's going to take the beach
of Troy with 50 men?

556
00:36:46.079 --> 00:36:48.665
Make way there!
Make way!

557
00:36:48.707 --> 00:36:50.709
( gong ringing distantly )

558
00:36:58.884 --> 00:37:01.302
Tecton.

559
00:37:01.344 --> 00:37:02.804
Is the Apollonian Guard ready?

560
00:37:02.846 --> 00:37:03.930
Waiting at the city gates.

561
00:37:03.972 --> 00:37:05.140
Good.
I'll be right there.

562
00:37:06.641 --> 00:37:08.309
Lysander.

563
00:37:08.351 --> 00:37:09.895
How long before
the army is ready?

564
00:37:09.936 --> 00:37:11.897
Half of our men are still coming
in from the countryside.

565
00:37:11.938 --> 00:37:14.107
We have to arm them,
we have to match them...
How long?

566
00:37:14.149 --> 00:37:14.816
Noon.

567
00:37:14.858 --> 00:37:15.567
Make it sooner.

568
00:37:19.571 --> 00:37:21.907
( distant yell )

569
00:37:24.617 --> 00:37:26.870
( rowers grunting )

570
00:37:28.121 --> 00:37:30.165
Patroclus!

571
00:37:30.207 --> 00:37:32.709
( man shouting,
rowers chanting )

572
00:37:32.751 --> 00:37:34.586
Put down your spear.

573
00:37:34.627 --> 00:37:36.171
But I'm fighting
the Trojans, cousin.

574
00:37:36.213 --> 00:37:37.338
Not today.

575
00:37:37.380 --> 00:37:38.339
But I'm ready.

576
00:37:38.381 --> 00:37:39.465
You taught me how to fight.

577
00:37:39.507 --> 00:37:40.800
And you're a good student.

578
00:37:40.842 --> 00:37:42.510
But you're not
a Myrmidon yet.

579
00:37:45.346 --> 00:37:46.890
Look at these men.

580
00:37:46.932 --> 00:37:49.017
They are the fiercest
soldiers in all of Greece.

581
00:37:49.059 --> 00:37:51.352
Each of them
has bled for me.

582
00:37:51.394 --> 00:37:52.687
You will guard
the ship.

583
00:37:52.729 --> 00:37:53.939
But this is a war!

584
00:37:53.980 --> 00:37:55.273
Cousin, I
can't fight

585
00:37:55.314 --> 00:37:56.900
the Trojans if I'm
concerned for you.

586
00:37:56.942 --> 00:37:57.943
Guard the ship.

587
00:37:59.569 --> 00:38:02.072
( grunts )

588
00:38:07.786 --> 00:38:10.705
( shouting )

589
00:38:16.711 --> 00:38:18.671
( horse neighing )

590
00:38:18.713 --> 00:38:20.924
HECTOR:
Trojans!

591
00:38:23.300 --> 00:38:26.721
All my life,
I've lived by a code.

592
00:38:26.763 --> 00:38:28.848
And the code is simple--

593
00:38:28.890 --> 00:38:31.893
honor the gods,
love your woman,

594
00:38:31.935 --> 00:38:34.311
and defend your country.

595
00:38:34.353 --> 00:38:35.855
( cheering )

596
00:38:35.897 --> 00:38:38.650
Troy is mother to us all.

597
00:38:38.691 --> 00:38:40.568
Fight for her!

598
00:38:40.610 --> 00:38:41.778
( cheering )

599
00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:44.114
( shouting )

600
00:38:53.748 --> 00:38:55.834
♪ ♪

601
00:38:59.671 --> 00:39:01.131
Myrmidons,

602
00:39:01.173 --> 00:39:05.510
my brothers of the sword.

603
00:39:05.551 --> 00:39:08.638
I'd rather fight beside you
than any army of thousands.

604
00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:10.431
Let no man forget

605
00:39:10.473 --> 00:39:11.683
how menacing we are.

606
00:39:11.724 --> 00:39:12.934
We are lions!

607
00:39:12.976 --> 00:39:14.019
( chanting )

608
00:39:15.478 --> 00:39:21.318
Do you know what's there,
waiting, beyond that beach?

609
00:39:21.358 --> 00:39:22.610
Immortality!

610
00:39:22.652 --> 00:39:23.778
Take it!

611
00:39:23.820 --> 00:39:24.946
It's yours!

612
00:39:24.988 --> 00:39:26.531
( shouting )

613
00:39:32.162 --> 00:39:35.040
( shouting )

614
00:39:35.081 --> 00:39:37.792
( men grunting and chanting )

615
00:39:37.834 --> 00:39:38.835
( man shouting )

616
00:39:38.877 --> 00:39:41.713
( men grunting )

617
00:39:41.754 --> 00:39:44.174
( man shouting )

618
00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:55.393
( grunting )

619
00:39:55.434 --> 00:39:58.021
( man shouting )

620
00:39:58.063 --> 00:40:02.567
( grunting )

621
00:40:02.608 --> 00:40:03.400
Forward!

622
00:40:03.442 --> 00:40:05.153
( grunting )

623
00:40:05.195 --> 00:40:06.487
( yelling )

624
00:40:09.115 --> 00:40:10.700
MAN:
Go!

625
00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:18.917
( grunting )

626
00:40:22.921 --> 00:40:25.048
( men shouting )

627
00:40:27.300 --> 00:40:29.552
The man wants to die.

628
00:40:41.356 --> 00:40:45.902
( grunting chant )

629
00:40:49.864 --> 00:40:51.449
ACHILLES:
On my command!

630
00:40:56.913 --> 00:40:57.956
( yelling )

631
00:40:57.997 --> 00:41:00.417
Break off! Break off!

632
00:41:00.458 --> 00:41:03.128
( men yelling )

633
00:41:11.469 --> 00:41:13.430
( metal clanging )

634
00:41:13.471 --> 00:41:15.765
( screaming, grunting )

635
00:41:32.531 --> 00:41:34.993
( rowers chanting )

636
00:41:40.039 --> 00:41:41.291
Look at him.

637
00:41:42.375 --> 00:41:43.376
Look.

638
00:41:45.544 --> 00:41:48.298
Row, you lazy
whores, row!

639
00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:50.342
Greeks are dying!

640
00:41:50.383 --> 00:41:51.759
Row!

641
00:41:52.969 --> 00:41:53.845
( screams )

642
00:41:53.886 --> 00:41:54.929
( grunts )

643
00:41:54.971 --> 00:41:58.683
( grunts and screams )

644
00:42:00.893 --> 00:42:01.686
( yelling )

645
00:42:07.317 --> 00:42:09.402
( horse neighing )

646
00:42:16.201 --> 00:42:19.037
( grunting )

647
00:42:19.078 --> 00:42:20.997
Those men down there need help.
Now!

648
00:42:21.039 --> 00:42:22.332
Tecton, with me.

649
00:42:26.585 --> 00:42:31.049
( grunts )

650
00:42:31.090 --> 00:42:32.675
Flank, Tecton!

651
00:42:35.928 --> 00:42:38.681
( panting )

652
00:42:41.184 --> 00:42:45.313
( grunts )

653
00:42:49.442 --> 00:42:51.903
( grunts )

654
00:42:58.576 --> 00:43:00.328
( panting )

655
00:43:00.370 --> 00:43:02.455
( grunting )

656
00:43:06.876 --> 00:43:09.754
( men chanting )

657
00:43:14.217 --> 00:43:18.096
Achilles! Achilles! Achilles...!

658
00:43:18.137 --> 00:43:19.347
Achilles!

659
00:43:19.389 --> 00:43:21.349
( men chanting )

660
00:43:21.391 --> 00:43:24.810
( grunting )

661
00:43:37.031 --> 00:43:38.157
( screaming )

662
00:43:41.953 --> 00:43:44.663
( men cheering and chanting )

663
00:43:51.170 --> 00:43:54.507
Back to the city!
Back to the city!

664
00:44:01.680 --> 00:44:05.768
The sun god is a patron of Troy,
our enemy.

665
00:44:05.810 --> 00:44:08.729
Take whatever treasure
you can find.

666
00:44:08.771 --> 00:44:11.774
( cheering )

667
00:44:13.443 --> 00:44:15.612
EUDORUS:
With your permission, my lord.

668
00:44:20.366 --> 00:44:21.117
Speak.

669
00:44:21.159 --> 00:44:23.119
Apollo sees everything.

670
00:44:23.161 --> 00:44:25.622
Perhaps... perhaps
it is not wise

671
00:44:25.663 --> 00:44:27.748
to offend him.

672
00:44:38.134 --> 00:44:40.428
( distant yells )

673
00:44:48.603 --> 00:44:51.230
Warn the men.

674
00:44:51.272 --> 00:44:53.316
Wait.

675
00:45:22.011 --> 00:45:23.012
( yells )

676
00:46:01.217 --> 00:46:02.468
( grunting )

677
00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:03.511
( men yelling )

678
00:46:03.553 --> 00:46:05.221
( grunting )

679
00:46:07.223 --> 00:46:11.060
( grunting )

680
00:46:12.604 --> 00:46:14.272
( yelling )

681
00:46:14.313 --> 00:46:15.981
( men shouting )

682
00:46:24.616 --> 00:46:26.618
ACHILLES:
You're very brave

683
00:46:26.659 --> 00:46:30.204
or very stupid to
come after me alone.

684
00:46:30.246 --> 00:46:33.249
You must be Hector.

685
00:46:39.672 --> 00:46:41.215
Do you know who I am?

686
00:46:41.257 --> 00:46:43.259
These priests weren't armed.

687
00:46:47.012 --> 00:46:48.264
Fight me!

688
00:46:53.936 --> 00:46:57.106
Why kill you now,
Prince of Troy,

689
00:46:57.148 --> 00:46:58.733
with no one here

690
00:46:58.775 --> 00:47:00.401
to see you fall?

691
00:47:11.203 --> 00:47:12.413
Why did you come here?

692
00:47:12.455 --> 00:47:13.830
They'll be talking
about this war

693
00:47:13.872 --> 00:47:14.873
for a thousand years.

694
00:47:14.915 --> 00:47:16.208
In a thousand years,

695
00:47:16.250 --> 00:47:18.586
the dust from our bones
will be gone.

696
00:47:18.628 --> 00:47:19.836
Yes, Prince.

697
00:47:19.878 --> 00:47:21.213
But our names will remain.

698
00:47:21.255 --> 00:47:23.299
( panting )

699
00:47:30.014 --> 00:47:31.683
( sighs )

700
00:47:31.724 --> 00:47:33.434
Go home, Prince.

701
00:47:33.476 --> 00:47:35.436
Drink some wine,
make love to your wife.

702
00:47:35.478 --> 00:47:37.814
Tomorrow, we'll have our war.

703
00:47:40.399 --> 00:47:42.527
You speak of war
as if it's a game.

704
00:47:42.568 --> 00:47:44.612
But how many wives wait
at Troy's gates

705
00:47:44.654 --> 00:47:46.656
for husbands
they'll never see again?

706
00:47:46.698 --> 00:47:48.700
Perhaps your brother
can comfort them.

707
00:47:48.741 --> 00:47:50.827
I hear he's good
at charming other men's wives.

708
00:47:54.664 --> 00:47:55.914
( blowing air through teeth )

709
00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:06.676
My lord, you
let him go?

710
00:48:09.345 --> 00:48:12.014
It's too early in the day
for killing princes.

711
00:48:22.483 --> 00:48:25.653
♪ ♪

712
00:48:37.998 --> 00:48:40.752
( cheering )

713
00:48:45.715 --> 00:48:47.216
( chanting ):
Achilles, Achilles...

714
00:48:53.723 --> 00:48:55.850
♪ ♪

715
00:49:18.955 --> 00:49:20.124
Achilles.

716
00:49:20.165 --> 00:49:22.126
Ajax.

717
00:49:22.167 --> 00:49:24.128
You're as fearless
as the gods.

718
00:49:24.169 --> 00:49:26.714
I'm honored to go
to war with you.

719
00:49:26.756 --> 00:49:28.006
As am I.

720
00:49:29.842 --> 00:49:31.886
If you sailed any slower,
the war would be over.

721
00:49:31.928 --> 00:49:34.639
I don't mind missing the start
as long as I'm here at the end.

722
00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:35.932
( laughs )
My lord.

723
00:49:35.972 --> 00:49:39.560
I've got something
to show you.

724
00:49:56.786 --> 00:50:00.623
The men found her
hiding in the temple.

725
00:50:00.665 --> 00:50:02.249
They thought she'd, um...

726
00:50:02.291 --> 00:50:03.417
( clears throat )

727
00:50:03.459 --> 00:50:04.961
...amuse you.

728
00:50:15.805 --> 00:50:18.140
What's your name?

729
00:50:21.769 --> 00:50:24.856
Did you not hear me?

730
00:50:24.897 --> 00:50:27.149
You killed Apollo's priests.

731
00:50:27.191 --> 00:50:28.609
I've killed men
in five countries,

732
00:50:28.651 --> 00:50:29.819
never a priest.

733
00:50:29.861 --> 00:50:31.153
Well, then your men did.

734
00:50:31.195 --> 00:50:34.072
The sun god will
have his vengeance.

735
00:50:34.114 --> 00:50:36.241
What is he waiting for?

736
00:50:36.283 --> 00:50:37.618
The right time to strike.

737
00:50:39.745 --> 00:50:42.456
His priests are dead,
and his acolytes are captive.

738
00:50:42.498 --> 00:50:44.458
I think your god
is afraid of me.

739
00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:45.751
Afraid?

740
00:50:45.793 --> 00:50:47.378
Apollo is master of the sun.

741
00:50:47.419 --> 00:50:48.546
He fears nothing.

742
00:50:48.587 --> 00:50:49.547
Then where is he?

743
00:50:49.588 --> 00:50:51.799
And you're nothing but a killer!

744
00:50:51.841 --> 00:50:53.926
You wouldn't know anything
about the gods.

745
00:50:54.969 --> 00:50:56.428
( sighs )

746
00:50:56.470 --> 00:50:59.557
I know more about the gods
than your priests.

747
00:50:59.598 --> 00:51:01.642
I've seen them.

748
00:51:06.898 --> 00:51:08.983
You're royalty, aren't you?

749
00:51:11.318 --> 00:51:14.279
Spent years talking down to men.

750
00:51:15.322 --> 00:51:17.742
( sniffs )

751
00:51:17.783 --> 00:51:19.911
You must be royalty.

752
00:51:21.871 --> 00:51:23.748
What's your name?

753
00:51:29.045 --> 00:51:32.339
Even the servants
of Apollo have names.

754
00:51:34.132 --> 00:51:36.134
Briseis.

755
00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:40.848
Are you afraid,
Briseis?

756
00:51:40.890 --> 00:51:42.892
Should I be?

757
00:51:46.228 --> 00:51:48.230
My lord.

758
00:51:49.982 --> 00:51:53.069
Agamemnon requests
your presence.

759
00:51:53.109 --> 00:51:55.613
The kings are gathering
to celebrate the victory.

760
00:51:58.616 --> 00:52:01.869
You fought well today.

761
00:52:01.911 --> 00:52:03.704
My lord.

762
00:52:08.500 --> 00:52:11.378
What do you want
here in Troy?

763
00:52:11.420 --> 00:52:13.589
You didn't come for
the Spartan queen.

764
00:52:13.631 --> 00:52:15.674
I want what all men want.

765
00:52:15.716 --> 00:52:17.718
I just want it more.

766
00:52:24.058 --> 00:52:26.727
You don't need
to fear me, girl.

767
00:52:26.769 --> 00:52:29.021
You're the only Trojan
who can say that.

768
00:52:34.860 --> 00:52:36.654
( goat bleating )

769
00:52:38.363 --> 00:52:39.824
( man shouting )

770
00:53:00.928 --> 00:53:03.014
You have won
a great victory,

771
00:53:03.055 --> 00:53:05.141
my king of kings.

772
00:53:05.181 --> 00:53:07.852
No one thought
the Trojan beach

773
00:53:07.893 --> 00:53:10.021
could be captured
so easily.

774
00:53:10.062 --> 00:53:12.064
A beautiful gift, Triopas.

775
00:53:13.774 --> 00:53:15.191
You will be
among the first

776
00:53:15.233 --> 00:53:17.028
to walk in the streets
of Troy tomorrow.

777
00:53:21.949 --> 00:53:24.576
My father, Naleus,
had this urn made

778
00:53:24.618 --> 00:53:25.953
to commemorate his victory

779
00:53:25.995 --> 00:53:27.121
at Cyparisseis.

780
00:53:27.163 --> 00:53:28.956
I present it to you

781
00:53:28.998 --> 00:53:31.125
in honor of an even
more memorable victory.

782
00:53:31.167 --> 00:53:34.294
AGAMEMNON:
Thank you, old friend.

783
00:53:34.336 --> 00:53:36.505
Tomorrow, we'll eat supper

784
00:53:36.547 --> 00:53:38.382
in the gardens of Troy.

785
00:53:43.971 --> 00:53:46.015
Leave us.

786
00:53:53.856 --> 00:53:57.651
War is young men dying,
and old men talking.

787
00:53:57.693 --> 00:53:58.652
You know this.

788
00:53:58.694 --> 00:54:00.487
Ignore the politics.

789
00:54:17.546 --> 00:54:20.132
Apparently,
you won some great victory.

790
00:54:20.174 --> 00:54:22.927
Ah, perhaps you didn't notice.

791
00:54:22.968 --> 00:54:24.970
The Trojan beach belonged
to Priam in the morning.

792
00:54:25.012 --> 00:54:27.806
It belongs to Agamemnon

793
00:54:27.848 --> 00:54:29.391
in the afternoon.

794
00:54:29.433 --> 00:54:31.518
You can have the beach.
I didn't come here for sand.

795
00:54:31.560 --> 00:54:34.688
No, you came here
because you want your name

796
00:54:34.730 --> 00:54:38.358
to last through
the ages.

797
00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:41.153
A great victory was won today.

798
00:54:41.195 --> 00:54:44.031
But that victory
is not yours.

799
00:54:44.073 --> 00:54:46.784
Kings did not kneel
to Achilles.

800
00:54:46.825 --> 00:54:50.037
Kings did not
pay homage to Achilles.

801
00:54:50.079 --> 00:54:52.206
Perhaps the kings were too far
behind to see.

802
00:54:52.248 --> 00:54:53.749
The soldiers won the battle.

803
00:54:53.791 --> 00:55:00.380
History remembers
kings, not soldiers!

804
00:55:00.422 --> 00:55:03.134
Tomorrow, we'll batter
down the gates of Troy.

805
00:55:03.175 --> 00:55:04.676
I'll build monuments
to victory

806
00:55:04.718 --> 00:55:06.053
on every island
of Greece.

807
00:55:06.095 --> 00:55:09.056
I'll carve Agamemnon
in the stone.

808
00:55:09.098 --> 00:55:10.099
Be careful,

809
00:55:10.141 --> 00:55:11.892
king of kings.

810
00:55:11.934 --> 00:55:13.602
First, you need the victory.

811
00:55:17.606 --> 00:55:18.690
Your men sacked

812
00:55:18.732 --> 00:55:20.692
the temple of Apollo, yes?

813
00:55:20.734 --> 00:55:22.611
You want gold, take it.

814
00:55:22.653 --> 00:55:24.696
It's my gift
to honor your courage.

815
00:55:24.738 --> 00:55:25.739
Take what you wish.

816
00:55:25.781 --> 00:55:27.116
I already have.

817
00:55:29.868 --> 00:55:32.037
Aphareus!

818
00:55:32.079 --> 00:55:34.165
Haemon!

819
00:55:35.833 --> 00:55:37.835
( Briseis grunting )

820
00:55:39.461 --> 00:55:40.587
( grunting )

821
00:55:40.629 --> 00:55:42.214
( sniffling )

822
00:55:42.256 --> 00:55:44.091
The spoils of war.

823
00:55:44.133 --> 00:55:45.884
I have no argument with you,
brothers,

824
00:55:45.926 --> 00:55:48.262
but if you don't release her,
you'll never see home again.

825
00:55:48.304 --> 00:55:49.429
Decide.

826
00:55:49.471 --> 00:55:50.222
Guards!

827
00:55:50.264 --> 00:55:51.140
( blades clang )

828
00:55:52.432 --> 00:55:54.268
Stop!

829
00:55:56.312 --> 00:55:58.314
Too many men have died today.

830
00:56:00.607 --> 00:56:02.276
If killing is your only talent,

831
00:56:02.318 --> 00:56:05.112
that's your curse.

832
00:56:05.154 --> 00:56:07.031
I don't want anyone
dying for me.

833
00:56:13.871 --> 00:56:16.456
AGAMEMNON:
Mighty Achilles,

834
00:56:16.498 --> 00:56:18.876
silenced by a slave girl.

835
00:56:21.337 --> 00:56:23.130
Tonight...

836
00:56:23.172 --> 00:56:25.423
I'll have her
give me a bath.

837
00:56:25.465 --> 00:56:27.634
And then...

838
00:56:27.676 --> 00:56:30.386
who knows?

839
00:56:30.428 --> 00:56:32.139
You sack of wine!

840
00:56:33.932 --> 00:56:36.476
Before my time is done,

841
00:56:36.518 --> 00:56:39.104
I will look down
on your corpse and smile.

842
00:56:41.857 --> 00:56:44.860
( indistinct shouting )

843
00:56:47.071 --> 00:56:49.240
( waves crashing )

844
00:56:53.202 --> 00:56:56.747
If they want a war,
we will give them a war.

845
00:56:56.788 --> 00:56:57.956
( crowd murmuring )

846
00:56:57.998 --> 00:57:00.500
I would match
the best of Troy

847
00:57:00.542 --> 00:57:03.254
against the best
of Greece any day.

848
00:57:03.295 --> 00:57:06.798
The best of Greece outnumber
the best of Troy two to one.

849
00:57:06.840 --> 00:57:08.926
( murmuring )

850
00:57:08.967 --> 00:57:11.053
Glaucus...

851
00:57:11.095 --> 00:57:13.222
you have fought with me
for 40 years.

852
00:57:13.264 --> 00:57:15.266
Can we win this war?

853
00:57:15.307 --> 00:57:17.809
Our walls have never
been breached.

854
00:57:17.851 --> 00:57:20.604
We have the finest
archers in the world.

855
00:57:20.645 --> 00:57:23.023
And we have Hector.

856
00:57:23.065 --> 00:57:24.524
Yes...

857
00:57:24.566 --> 00:57:25.984
we can win.

858
00:57:26.026 --> 00:57:27.361
( clapping and cheering )

859
00:57:31.573 --> 00:57:34.201
I spoke to two farmers today.

860
00:57:34.243 --> 00:57:37.662
They saw an eagle
flying with a serpent

861
00:57:37.704 --> 00:57:40.040
clutched in its talons.

862
00:57:40.082 --> 00:57:43.335
This is a sign from Apollo.

863
00:57:43.377 --> 00:57:45.712
We will win a great victory
tomorrow.

864
00:57:45.754 --> 00:57:47.298
Bird signs.

865
00:57:47.339 --> 00:57:50.259
You want to plan a strategy
based on bird signs.

866
00:57:50.301 --> 00:57:52.136
PRIAM:
Hector, show respect.

867
00:57:52.177 --> 00:57:55.097
A high priest is
a servant of the gods.

868
00:57:55.139 --> 00:57:58.434
And I am a servant of Troy.

869
00:57:58.474 --> 00:58:01.228
I've always honored the gods,
Father, you know that.

870
00:58:01.270 --> 00:58:03.397
But today I fought
a Greek who desecrated

871
00:58:03.439 --> 00:58:05.065
the statue of Apollo.

872
00:58:05.107 --> 00:58:07.359
Apollo didn't strike
the man down.

873
00:58:08.735 --> 00:58:11.280
The gods won't fight
this war for us.

874
00:58:11.322 --> 00:58:13.240
There won't be a war.

875
00:58:13.282 --> 00:58:15.284
( crowd murmurs )

876
00:58:18.287 --> 00:58:20.664
This is not a conflict
of nations.

877
00:58:20.705 --> 00:58:23.083
It is a dispute between two men.

878
00:58:23.125 --> 00:58:26.753
And I don't want to see another
Trojan die because of me.

879
00:58:26.795 --> 00:58:27.629
Paris!

880
00:58:28.880 --> 00:58:31.425
Tomorrow morning,
I will challenge Menelaus

881
00:58:31.467 --> 00:58:32.968
for the right to Helen.

882
00:58:33.010 --> 00:58:35.137
The winner will
take her home.

883
00:58:35.179 --> 00:58:38.265
The loser will burn
before nightfall.

884
00:58:47.732 --> 00:58:49.734
♪ ♪

885
00:58:56.950 --> 00:58:59.786
PARIS:
Father...

886
00:58:59.828 --> 00:59:03.290
I'm sorry for the pain
I've caused you.

887
00:59:03.332 --> 00:59:07.085
Do you love her?

888
00:59:07.127 --> 00:59:09.629
You are a great king

889
00:59:09.671 --> 00:59:12.548
because you love
your country so much.

890
00:59:12.590 --> 00:59:15.635
Every blade of grass.

891
00:59:15.677 --> 00:59:17.429
Every grain of sand.

892
00:59:17.471 --> 00:59:19.473
Every rock in the river.

893
00:59:19.515 --> 00:59:23.352
You love all of Troy.

894
00:59:25.312 --> 00:59:27.523
That is the way
I love Helen.

895
00:59:29.774 --> 00:59:34.196
PRIAM:
I've fought many wars
in my time.

896
00:59:34.238 --> 00:59:36.198
Some were fought for land,

897
00:59:36.240 --> 00:59:40.618
some for power,
some for glory.

898
00:59:40.660 --> 00:59:43.288
I suppose fighting for love

899
00:59:43.330 --> 00:59:46.750
makes more sense
than all the rest,

900
00:59:46.791 --> 00:59:49.711
but I won't be
the one fighting.

901
00:59:52.797 --> 00:59:54.758
The sword of Troy.

902
00:59:54.799 --> 00:59:59.096
My father carried this sword,
and his father before him,

903
00:59:59.137 --> 01:00:01.973
all the way back
to the founding of Troy.

904
01:00:02.015 --> 01:00:06.353
The history of our people
was written with this sword.

905
01:00:08.355 --> 01:00:11.108
Carry it with you tomorrow.

906
01:00:14.069 --> 01:00:18.156
The spirit of Troy
is in that sword.

907
01:00:18.198 --> 01:00:22.119
So long as a Trojan
carries it,

908
01:00:22.160 --> 01:00:25.497
our people have
a future.

909
01:00:27.165 --> 01:00:32.963
The man who killed Tecton
outside Apollo's temple--

910
01:00:33.004 --> 01:00:35.799
I've never seen a spear
thrown like that.

911
01:00:35.840 --> 01:00:38.427
An impossible throw.

912
01:00:42.973 --> 01:00:46.101
Don't go tomorrow.

913
01:00:46.143 --> 01:00:47.978
Please don't go.

914
01:00:48.019 --> 01:00:50.272
Paris fights tomorrow, not me.

915
01:00:50.314 --> 01:00:51.856
50,000 Greeks
didn't cross the sea

916
01:00:51.898 --> 01:00:53.317
to watch your brother fight.

917
01:00:53.358 --> 01:00:54.610
You know this.

918
01:00:54.650 --> 01:00:57.404
You'd make a fine general,
my love.

919
01:00:57.446 --> 01:01:00.115
You've been fighting
your whole life.

920
01:01:00.157 --> 01:01:02.117
Let other men do
battle this time.

921
01:01:02.159 --> 01:01:04.953
You know I don't want to fight.

922
01:01:04.995 --> 01:01:07.414
I want to see my son
grow tall.

923
01:01:07.456 --> 01:01:09.707
I want to see the girls
chasing after him.

924
01:01:09.749 --> 01:01:13.545
I can't lose you.

925
01:01:13.587 --> 01:01:18.008
I won't survive.

926
01:01:18.049 --> 01:01:20.051
( crying )

927
01:01:29.978 --> 01:01:31.938
♪ ♪

928
01:01:31.980 --> 01:01:34.650
I must see Paris.

929
01:01:41.448 --> 01:01:43.908
Wait.

930
01:01:43.950 --> 01:01:45.702
Wait!

931
01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:52.543
Helen... what
are you doing?

932
01:01:52.584 --> 01:01:53.669
Let me go.

933
01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:56.213
No.

934
01:01:56.254 --> 01:01:58.798
( crying )

935
01:01:58.840 --> 01:02:01.552
( sighs )

936
01:02:01.593 --> 01:02:03.512
I saw them burn.

937
01:02:03.554 --> 01:02:05.013
( sniffles )

938
01:02:05.055 --> 01:02:08.016
I saw them burning on the pyres.

939
01:02:10.060 --> 01:02:12.770
That's my fault.

940
01:02:12.812 --> 01:02:17.275
It is.
You know it is.

941
01:02:17.317 --> 01:02:20.362
All those widows.

942
01:02:20.404 --> 01:02:24.074
I still hear them screaming.

943
01:02:24.115 --> 01:02:28.370
Their husbands died
because I'm here.

944
01:02:28.412 --> 01:02:30.372
I'm going down to the ships.

945
01:02:30.414 --> 01:02:32.332
No, you're not.

946
01:02:32.374 --> 01:02:33.750
I'm giving myself
back to Menelaus.

947
01:02:33.791 --> 01:02:35.919
It's too late for that.

948
01:02:35.960 --> 01:02:39.339
Do you think Agamemnon cares
about his brother's marriage?

949
01:02:39.381 --> 01:02:41.883
This is about power,
not love.

950
01:02:41.925 --> 01:02:44.261
Paris is going to fight
in the morning?

951
01:02:45.345 --> 01:02:46.888
Yes.

952
01:02:46.930 --> 01:02:48.390
Menelaus will kill him.

953
01:02:48.432 --> 01:02:49.974
I won't let that happen.

954
01:02:50.016 --> 01:02:51.560
It's his decision.

955
01:02:51.602 --> 01:02:52.686
No.

956
01:02:52.728 --> 01:02:55.313
I can't ask anyone
to fight for me.

957
01:02:56.773 --> 01:02:59.276
I'm no longer
queen of Sparta.

958
01:03:01.361 --> 01:03:04.698
You're a princess
of Troy now...

959
01:03:04.740 --> 01:03:07.784
and my brother
needs you tonight.

960
01:03:20.464 --> 01:03:22.758
( indistinct chatter )

961
01:03:34.060 --> 01:03:36.062
My lord.

962
01:03:40.233 --> 01:03:42.319
My lord, the army
is marching.

963
01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:45.322
Let them march.
We stay.

964
01:03:45.363 --> 01:03:46.906
But the men are ready.

965
01:03:46.948 --> 01:03:49.200
We stay till Agamemnon groans
to have Achilles back.

966
01:03:49.242 --> 01:03:51.745
As you wish.

967
01:04:02.506 --> 01:04:04.800
Are you ready to fight?

968
01:04:04.840 --> 01:04:07.302
Are you ready to kill?
To take life?

969
01:04:07.344 --> 01:04:09.346
I am.

970
01:04:13.684 --> 01:04:18.772
At night, I see their faces,
all the men I've killed.

971
01:04:18.814 --> 01:04:22.900
They're standing there on
the far bank of the River Styx.

972
01:04:24.902 --> 01:04:28.657
They're waiting for me.

973
01:04:28.699 --> 01:04:30.867
They say, "Welcome, brother."

974
01:04:37.915 --> 01:04:40.168
We men are wretched things.

975
01:04:43.254 --> 01:04:45.965
I taught you how to fight,
but I never taught you

976
01:04:46.007 --> 01:04:47.718
why to fight.

977
01:04:47.759 --> 01:04:49.427
I fight for you.

978
01:04:49.469 --> 01:04:51.596
Who will you fight for
when I'm gone?

979
01:04:54.140 --> 01:04:56.727
Soldiers, they fight for kings
they've never even met.

980
01:04:56.768 --> 01:04:59.103
They do what
they're told;

981
01:04:59.145 --> 01:05:01.231
they die when
they're told to die.

982
01:05:01.272 --> 01:05:02.940
Soldiers obey.

983
01:05:05.151 --> 01:05:08.196
Don't waste your life
following some fool's orders.

984
01:05:11.533 --> 01:05:13.702
Go.

985
01:05:19.999 --> 01:05:22.168
♪ ♪

986
01:05:27.424 --> 01:05:29.718
( man shouts )

987
01:05:29.760 --> 01:05:31.927
( men shouting )

988
01:05:31.969 --> 01:05:33.971
♪ ♪

989
01:05:35.014 --> 01:05:37.350
( horses galloping )

990
01:05:38.685 --> 01:05:41.104
( men shouting in distance )

991
01:05:50.572 --> 01:05:53.825
♪ ♪

992
01:06:03.585 --> 01:06:05.921
♪ ♪

993
01:06:16.972 --> 01:06:19.684
( horse neighs in distance )

994
01:06:19.726 --> 01:06:21.728
( Helen gasps softly )

995
01:06:29.193 --> 01:06:32.363
( barely audible shouts
in distance )

996
01:06:37.994 --> 01:06:41.205
Are you sure
you want to do this?

997
01:06:41.247 --> 01:06:43.750
I started this war.

998
01:06:58.765 --> 01:06:59.891
Helen.

999
01:07:01.935 --> 01:07:03.520
Sit with me.

1000
01:07:13.363 --> 01:07:15.365
( horse neighs )

1001
01:07:31.589 --> 01:07:34.091
( ground rumbling )

1002
01:07:40.015 --> 01:07:43.518
( man shouting )

1003
01:07:52.151 --> 01:07:55.613
( man shouts )

1004
01:08:05.331 --> 01:08:08.001
♪ ♪

1005
01:08:17.052 --> 01:08:19.387
♪ ♪

1006
01:08:21.723 --> 01:08:24.225
( horse neighs )

1007
01:08:50.627 --> 01:08:53.379
( exhales )

1008
01:09:04.390 --> 01:09:07.393
♪ ♪

1009
01:09:07.435 --> 01:09:10.605
( man shouts )

1010
01:09:19.363 --> 01:09:21.908
( man shouts )

1011
01:09:21.950 --> 01:09:23.994
Prepare to halt!

1012
01:09:24.035 --> 01:09:25.787
Halt!

1013
01:09:29.582 --> 01:09:31.584
( horse neighs )

1014
01:09:44.806 --> 01:09:46.432
Move.

1015
01:09:52.188 --> 01:09:54.858
( crow cawing in distance )

1016
01:10:15.628 --> 01:10:18.673
I see you're not hiding
behind your high walls.

1017
01:10:18.715 --> 01:10:20.341
Valiant of you.

1018
01:10:20.383 --> 01:10:23.511
Ill-advised, but valiant.

1019
01:10:23.553 --> 01:10:25.429
You come here uninvited.

1020
01:10:25.471 --> 01:10:27.431
Go back to your ships
and go home.

1021
01:10:27.473 --> 01:10:29.350
We've come too far,
Prince Hector.

1022
01:10:29.392 --> 01:10:31.602
Prince? What prince?

1023
01:10:31.644 --> 01:10:34.689
What son of a king would accept
a man's hospitality,

1024
01:10:34.731 --> 01:10:36.858
eat his food,
drink his wine,

1025
01:10:36.900 --> 01:10:39.903
embrace him in friendship,
and then steal his wife
in the middle of the night?

1026
01:10:39.944 --> 01:10:42.155
The sun was shining
when your wife left you.

1027
01:10:43.740 --> 01:10:46.868
She's up there watching,
isn't she? Good.

1028
01:10:46.910 --> 01:10:49.328
I want her to watch you die.

1029
01:10:49.370 --> 01:10:50.997
AGAMEMNON:
Not yet,

1030
01:10:51.039 --> 01:10:53.248
brother.

1031
01:10:53.290 --> 01:10:55.585
Look around you, Hector.

1032
01:10:55.626 --> 01:10:58.838
I brought all the warriors
of Greece to your shores.

1033
01:10:58.880 --> 01:11:01.049
You can still save
Troy, young prince.

1034
01:11:01.091 --> 01:11:02.675
I have two wishes.

1035
01:11:02.717 --> 01:11:06.679
If you grant them, no more
of your people need die.

1036
01:11:06.721 --> 01:11:09.724
First, you must give Helen back
to my brother.

1037
01:11:09.766 --> 01:11:13.519
Second, Troy must submit
to my command

1038
01:11:13.561 --> 01:11:16.397
to fight for me
whenever I call.

1039
01:11:16.439 --> 01:11:19.817
You want me to look upon
your army and tremble?

1040
01:11:21.736 --> 01:11:23.613
Well, I see them.

1041
01:11:23.654 --> 01:11:28.618
I see 50,000 men brought here
to fight for one man's greed.

1042
01:11:32.247 --> 01:11:34.749
Careful, boy.

1043
01:11:34.791 --> 01:11:37.001
My mercy has limits.

1044
01:11:37.043 --> 01:11:39.503
And I've seen the limits
of your mercy.

1045
01:11:39.545 --> 01:11:41.547
And I tell you now,
no son of Troy

1046
01:11:41.589 --> 01:11:44.217
will ever submit
to a foreign ruler.

1047
01:11:44.259 --> 01:11:48.554
Then every son of Troy
shall die.

1048
01:11:51.682 --> 01:11:53.184
There is another way.

1049
01:11:55.436 --> 01:11:57.188
I love Helen.

1050
01:11:57.230 --> 01:11:59.523
I won't give her up
and neither will you.

1051
01:11:59.565 --> 01:12:01.943
So let us fight
our own battle.

1052
01:12:01.985 --> 01:12:03.903
The winner takes Helen home.

1053
01:12:03.945 --> 01:12:05.905
And let that be the end of it.

1054
01:12:05.947 --> 01:12:07.573
A brave offer,

1055
01:12:07.615 --> 01:12:09.784
but not enough.

1056
01:12:11.702 --> 01:12:13.163
Let me kill this
little peacock.

1057
01:12:13.204 --> 01:12:15.039
I didn't come here
for your pretty wife.

1058
01:12:15.957 --> 01:12:18.084
I came here for Troy.

1059
01:12:18.126 --> 01:12:20.753
And I came for my honor.

1060
01:12:20.795 --> 01:12:23.089
His every breath insults me.

1061
01:12:23.131 --> 01:12:24.966
Let me kill him.

1062
01:12:25.008 --> 01:12:27.135
When he's lying in the dust,
give the signal to attack.

1063
01:12:27.177 --> 01:12:28.385
You'll have your city.

1064
01:12:28.427 --> 01:12:30.180
I'll have my revenge.

1065
01:12:35.518 --> 01:12:37.312
So be it.

1066
01:12:41.356 --> 01:12:43.318
I accept your challenge,

1067
01:12:43.400 --> 01:12:45.862
and tonight
I'll drink to your bones.

1068
01:12:55.330 --> 01:12:56.455
MAN:
My lord.

1069
01:12:56.497 --> 01:12:59.375
AGAMEMNON:
Back to the line!

1070
01:13:00.501 --> 01:13:03.004
( men shout )

1071
01:13:06.716 --> 01:13:08.718
( sword clangs )

1072
01:13:13.097 --> 01:13:16.642
Make him swing and miss--
he'll tire.

1073
01:13:16.684 --> 01:13:18.644
Brother...

1074
01:13:18.686 --> 01:13:20.313
if I fall...

1075
01:13:20.355 --> 01:13:21.898
tell Helen, tell her...

1076
01:13:21.939 --> 01:13:23.233
I will.

1077
01:13:23.274 --> 01:13:26.069
Don't let Menelaus
hurt her. If he...

1078
01:13:26.110 --> 01:13:28.238
You think of your sword
and his sword

1079
01:13:28.279 --> 01:13:29.613
and nothing else.

1080
01:13:33.910 --> 01:13:36.662
( crows cawing in distance )

1081
01:13:45.213 --> 01:13:47.548
( sword clangs )

1082
01:13:50.426 --> 01:13:52.427
( sighs )

1083
01:14:19.496 --> 01:14:20.290
( chuckles )

1084
01:14:20.331 --> 01:14:24.419
( grunting )

1085
01:14:24.460 --> 01:14:27.880
( panting )

1086
01:14:38.808 --> 01:14:39.892
( grunts )

1087
01:14:41.018 --> 01:14:42.728
Get up.

1088
01:14:42.770 --> 01:14:44.314
Come on.

1089
01:14:44.355 --> 01:14:45.773
( laughs )

1090
01:14:45.815 --> 01:14:46.899
( laughing )

1091
01:14:48.318 --> 01:14:50.111
( laughs )

1092
01:14:50.153 --> 01:14:51.362
( blow lands, Paris grunts )

1093
01:14:51.404 --> 01:14:52.529
( swords clang )

1094
01:14:56.033 --> 01:14:57.743
( panting )

1095
01:15:04.959 --> 01:15:07.753
( laughing )

1096
01:15:09.588 --> 01:15:11.757
( groans in pain )
( low growl )

1097
01:15:14.927 --> 01:15:16.137
( low growl )

1098
01:15:18.348 --> 01:15:21.184
( swords clanging )

1099
01:15:22.352 --> 01:15:26.230
( gasping and groaning )

1100
01:15:30.067 --> 01:15:31.819
See the crows?

1101
01:15:33.654 --> 01:15:35.865
They never tasted
prince before.

1102
01:15:35.906 --> 01:15:38.284
( crows cawing in distance )

1103
01:15:38.326 --> 01:15:39.702
( grunts )

1104
01:15:56.760 --> 01:15:58.221
( low growl )

1105
01:16:10.149 --> 01:16:14.362
Is this...
what you left me for?!

1106
01:16:14.404 --> 01:16:15.488
Fight!

1107
01:16:15.530 --> 01:16:17.823
Fight me!

1108
01:16:17.865 --> 01:16:19.158
( Paris gasping )

1109
01:16:19.200 --> 01:16:20.535
You coward!

1110
01:16:20.576 --> 01:16:21.994
Fight me!

1111
01:16:22.036 --> 01:16:23.413
We have a pact!

1112
01:16:23.454 --> 01:16:24.539
Fight!

1113
01:16:24.579 --> 01:16:25.748
Fight him, son...

1114
01:16:25.789 --> 01:16:26.957
MENELAUS:
Coward!

1115
01:16:26.999 --> 01:16:28.125
...fight him.

1116
01:16:28.167 --> 01:16:29.460
MENELAUS:
Fight me!

1117
01:16:29.502 --> 01:16:31.003
The Trojans have violated
the agreement!

1118
01:16:31.045 --> 01:16:32.088
Fight!

1119
01:16:32.129 --> 01:16:33.588
Prepare for battle!

1120
01:16:36.384 --> 01:16:37.843
This is not honor!

1121
01:16:37.885 --> 01:16:40.555
This is not worthy of royalty!

1122
01:16:40.595 --> 01:16:42.848
If he doesn't fight,

1123
01:16:42.890 --> 01:16:44.016
Troy is doomed.

1124
01:16:44.058 --> 01:16:46.727
The fight is over.

1125
01:16:46.769 --> 01:16:48.438
The fight is not over.

1126
01:16:48.479 --> 01:16:50.273
Stand back, Prince Hector.

1127
01:16:50.314 --> 01:16:51.815
I'll kill him
at your feet.

1128
01:16:51.857 --> 01:16:52.942
I don't care!

1129
01:16:52.983 --> 01:16:54.569
He's my brother.

1130
01:16:54.609 --> 01:16:56.070
( panting )

1131
01:16:56.112 --> 01:16:57.238
( Menelaus yells )

1132
01:16:57.280 --> 01:16:59.282
( groans )

1133
01:17:02.743 --> 01:17:04.870
( grunts )

1134
01:17:04.912 --> 01:17:07.164
( groans weakly )

1135
01:17:09.542 --> 01:17:11.377
( grunts )

1136
01:17:16.340 --> 01:17:20.052
♪ ♪

1137
01:17:24.390 --> 01:17:27.184
( yells )

1138
01:17:27.226 --> 01:17:29.686
( all yelling )

1139
01:17:40.364 --> 01:17:42.032
( grunts )

1140
01:17:42.074 --> 01:17:43.159
Paris!

1141
01:17:52.251 --> 01:17:54.711
Go. Go.

1142
01:18:01.427 --> 01:18:03.012
Get inside, Paris!

1143
01:18:04.054 --> 01:18:05.264
Archers!

1144
01:18:08.559 --> 01:18:10.269
Our men are too close
to the walls.

1145
01:18:10.311 --> 01:18:12.229
Pull back, you fool!

1146
01:18:12.271 --> 01:18:13.730
For Troy!

1147
01:18:13.772 --> 01:18:15.774
ALL:
For Troy!

1148
01:18:21.364 --> 01:18:24.074
( shouting )

1149
01:18:34.293 --> 01:18:35.169
Now!

1150
01:18:35.211 --> 01:18:36.587
Loose!

1151
01:18:42.677 --> 01:18:44.512
( yelling and grunting )

1152
01:18:55.606 --> 01:18:58.817
♪ ♪

1153
01:19:04.990 --> 01:19:05.991
Get them in line!

1154
01:19:08.452 --> 01:19:11.497
Get the men back into lines!

1155
01:19:11.539 --> 01:19:14.041
Front line, push!

1156
01:19:14.083 --> 01:19:16.669
( grunts )

1157
01:19:26.929 --> 01:19:29.014
( yelling )

1158
01:19:37.814 --> 01:19:39.149
( yelling )

1159
01:19:48.783 --> 01:19:53.038
( yelling and groaning )

1160
01:20:02.839 --> 01:20:06.009
( groaning )

1161
01:20:14.977 --> 01:20:17.271
( yelling )

1162
01:20:22.735 --> 01:20:26.614
( grunting )

1163
01:20:37.333 --> 01:20:39.960
( yelling and grunting )

1164
01:20:50.638 --> 01:20:54.517
( Trojan soldiers cheering )

1165
01:20:59.814 --> 01:21:03.108
Forward. Forward!

1166
01:21:03.150 --> 01:21:04.193
( shouting )

1167
01:21:12.493 --> 01:21:13.703
( yelling )

1168
01:21:14.911 --> 01:21:16.455
Forward!

1169
01:21:19.500 --> 01:21:22.837
( grunting )

1170
01:21:28.008 --> 01:21:29.552
Apollonians!

1171
01:21:29.593 --> 01:21:33.013
( yelling )

1172
01:21:40.437 --> 01:21:41.689
( grunts )

1173
01:21:41.731 --> 01:21:42.565
Prince Hector!

1174
01:21:45.942 --> 01:21:47.820
Keep going!
We need to retreat!

1175
01:21:47.862 --> 01:21:50.406
AGAMEMNON:
My army has never
lost a battle yet!

1176
01:21:50.447 --> 01:21:53.701
You won't have an army
if you don't fall back!

1177
01:21:59.790 --> 01:22:01.958
Back to the ships!

1178
01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:03.669
Back to the ships!
Retreat!

1179
01:22:03.711 --> 01:22:07.005
Back! Go back!
Retreat!

1180
01:22:07.047 --> 01:22:09.550
( cheering )

1181
01:22:12.720 --> 01:22:14.179
Get back!
Get back to the ships!

1182
01:22:18.350 --> 01:22:21.687
( yelling )

1183
01:22:21.729 --> 01:22:23.647
( horses neighing )

1184
01:22:23.689 --> 01:22:27.067
( shouting )

1185
01:22:38.078 --> 01:22:41.081
( shouting )

1186
01:22:50.006 --> 01:22:52.050
♪ ♪

1187
01:22:58.098 --> 01:23:00.225
Fall back!

1188
01:23:00.267 --> 01:23:02.812
Men, fall back! Halt!

1189
01:23:02.853 --> 01:23:05.355
Go back!

1190
01:23:10.068 --> 01:23:11.612
Halt!

1191
01:23:11.654 --> 01:23:13.196
But, my prince,
we have them on the run!

1192
01:23:13.238 --> 01:23:14.907
We're in range of their archers.

1193
01:23:14.949 --> 01:23:17.660
Have our men
gather our fallen.

1194
01:23:17.701 --> 01:23:19.035
Send an emissary to the Greeks.

1195
01:23:19.077 --> 01:23:20.788
Tell them they can collect
their dead.

1196
01:23:20.830 --> 01:23:22.665
Would they have done
the same for us?

1197
01:23:26.460 --> 01:23:27.419
Go!

1198
01:23:27.461 --> 01:23:28.879
Back!

1199
01:23:28.921 --> 01:23:32.132
LYSANDER:
Fall back into line!

1200
01:23:40.390 --> 01:23:43.226
♪ ♪

1201
01:24:03.163 --> 01:24:06.667
♪ ♪

1202
01:24:14.800 --> 01:24:17.636
♪ ♪

1203
01:24:27.021 --> 01:24:30.691
♪ ♪

1204
01:24:40.283 --> 01:24:41.660
( gasps )

1205
01:24:41.702 --> 01:24:43.453
You think I'm a coward.

1206
01:24:45.664 --> 01:24:47.583
I am a coward.

1207
01:24:49.209 --> 01:24:51.503
I knew he would kill me.

1208
01:24:51.545 --> 01:24:53.881
You were watching.

1209
01:24:55.716 --> 01:24:58.092
My father...

1210
01:24:58.134 --> 01:24:59.511
my brother...

1211
01:24:59.553 --> 01:25:02.056
all of Troy.

1212
01:25:02.096 --> 01:25:04.140
Shame didn't matter.

1213
01:25:04.182 --> 01:25:09.479
I gave up my pride...
my honor...

1214
01:25:09.521 --> 01:25:11.815
...just to live.

1215
01:25:11.857 --> 01:25:14.276
For love.

1216
01:25:14.317 --> 01:25:16.110
You challenged
a great warrior.

1217
01:25:16.152 --> 01:25:17.988
That took courage.

1218
01:25:19.823 --> 01:25:21.909
I betrayed you.

1219
01:25:28.122 --> 01:25:30.751
Menelaus was a brave man.

1220
01:25:33.754 --> 01:25:36.172
He lived for fighting.

1221
01:25:39.969 --> 01:25:41.720
And every day
I was with him,

1222
01:25:41.762 --> 01:25:44.264
I wanted to walk into
the sea and drown.

1223
01:25:47.601 --> 01:25:49.937
I don't want a hero,
my love.

1224
01:25:49.979 --> 01:25:53.690
I want a man I
can grow old with.

1225
01:25:53.732 --> 01:25:56.526
They're laughing at me in Troy.

1226
01:25:56.568 --> 01:26:00.072
Drunk with victory!

1227
01:26:00.114 --> 01:26:03.158
They think I'll sail home
at first light.

1228
01:26:03.199 --> 01:26:05.077
Maybe we should.

1229
01:26:05.119 --> 01:26:07.454
Flee? Like a whipped dog?

1230
01:26:07.496 --> 01:26:10.833
The men believe we came here
for Menelaus's wife.

1231
01:26:12.292 --> 01:26:14.086
He won't be needing her anymore.

1232
01:26:14.128 --> 01:26:17.380
My brother's blood still wets
the sand, and you insult him!

1233
01:26:17.422 --> 01:26:20.216
It's no insult to say
a dead man is dead.

1234
01:26:20.258 --> 01:26:21.760
NESTOR:
If we leave now,

1235
01:26:21.802 --> 01:26:23.553
we lose all credibility.

1236
01:26:23.595 --> 01:26:25.889
If the Trojans can
beat us so easily,

1237
01:26:25.931 --> 01:26:28.433
how long before
the Hittites invade?

1238
01:26:28.475 --> 01:26:32.813
If we stay, we stay here
for the right reasons--

1239
01:26:32.855 --> 01:26:35.398
to protect Greece,
not your pride.

1240
01:26:35.440 --> 01:26:38.110
Your private battle with
Achilles is destroying us.

1241
01:26:38.152 --> 01:26:39.486
Achilles is one man.

1242
01:26:39.528 --> 01:26:42.447
Hector is one man.

1243
01:26:42.489 --> 01:26:44.116
Look what he did to us today.

1244
01:26:44.158 --> 01:26:46.618
Hector fights for his country!

1245
01:26:46.660 --> 01:26:48.328
Achilles fights only
for himself!

1246
01:26:48.370 --> 01:26:50.998
I don't care about
the man's allegiance,

1247
01:26:51.040 --> 01:26:53.167
I care about his ability
to win battles.

1248
01:26:53.207 --> 01:26:54.918
NESTOR:
He's right.

1249
01:26:54.960 --> 01:26:56.586
The men's morale is weak.

1250
01:26:56.628 --> 01:26:59.756
Well, even if I could make peace
with Achilles,

1251
01:26:59.798 --> 01:27:02.467
the man won't listen to me!

1252
01:27:02.509 --> 01:27:05.846
He's as likely to spear me
as to speak to me!

1253
01:27:07.221 --> 01:27:08.598
I'll talk to him.

1254
01:27:08.640 --> 01:27:10.225
He'll want the girl back.

1255
01:27:10.266 --> 01:27:12.061
He can have the damn girl.

1256
01:27:14.021 --> 01:27:15.731
I haven't touched her.

1257
01:27:15.772 --> 01:27:17.315
Where is she?

1258
01:27:17.357 --> 01:27:19.068
I gave her to the men.

1259
01:27:20.402 --> 01:27:25.949
They need some amusement
after today.

1260
01:27:25.991 --> 01:27:28.493
( soldiers laughing )

1261
01:27:28.535 --> 01:27:29.953
Come on, give the bitch to me!

1262
01:27:29.995 --> 01:27:32.081
Hey, who's first?

1263
01:27:32.122 --> 01:27:33.123
Here!

1264
01:27:33.165 --> 01:27:35.167
HAEMON:
Trojan whore!

1265
01:27:35.209 --> 01:27:37.377
What's this,
a virgin's robe?

1266
01:27:37.419 --> 01:27:39.088
You won't be needing that
for much longer!

1267
01:27:39.129 --> 01:27:41.381
Hold her!

1268
01:27:46.011 --> 01:27:47.846
Better to be a Spartan slave
than a Trojan...

1269
01:27:47.888 --> 01:27:48.931
Achilles!

1270
01:27:48.972 --> 01:27:51.892
( yells )

1271
01:28:03.237 --> 01:28:05.739
♪ ♪

1272
01:28:09.118 --> 01:28:12.370
( Briseis softly crying )

1273
01:28:19.086 --> 01:28:20.796
Are you hurt?

1274
01:28:27.343 --> 01:28:29.554
I watched you fight them,
you have courage.

1275
01:28:29.596 --> 01:28:32.057
To fight back
when people attack me--

1276
01:28:32.099 --> 01:28:34.768
dog has that kind of courage.

1277
01:28:49.199 --> 01:28:51.326
( splashing )

1278
01:28:57.874 --> 01:28:59.501
Eat.

1279
01:29:07.801 --> 01:29:09.803
I've known men like you
my whole life.

1280
01:29:11.387 --> 01:29:12.764
No, you haven't.

1281
01:29:12.806 --> 01:29:16.101
You think you're so different
from a thousand others?

1282
01:29:16.143 --> 01:29:18.603
Soldiers understand nothing
but war.

1283
01:29:18.645 --> 01:29:20.063
Peace confuses them.

1284
01:29:20.105 --> 01:29:21.273
And you hate these soldiers.

1285
01:29:21.315 --> 01:29:22.732
I pity them.

1286
01:29:22.774 --> 01:29:26.278
Trojan soldiers died
trying to protect you.

1287
01:29:26.320 --> 01:29:28.238
Perhaps they deserve
more than your pity.

1288
01:29:32.117 --> 01:29:34.077
Why did you choose this life?

1289
01:29:34.119 --> 01:29:35.245
What life?

1290
01:29:35.287 --> 01:29:36.788
To be a great warrior.

1291
01:29:39.041 --> 01:29:40.792
I chose nothing.

1292
01:29:40.834 --> 01:29:43.086
I was born, and
this is what I am.

1293
01:29:43.128 --> 01:29:47.716
And you? Why did you
choose to love a god?

1294
01:29:47.757 --> 01:29:51.553
I think you'll find
the romance one-sided.

1295
01:29:53.180 --> 01:29:55.849
Do you enjoy provoking me?

1296
01:29:57.475 --> 01:30:00.062
You've dedicated your life
to the gods--

1297
01:30:00.103 --> 01:30:01.104
Zeus, god of thunder,

1298
01:30:01.146 --> 01:30:02.647
Athena, goddess of wisdom.

1299
01:30:02.689 --> 01:30:03.648
You serve them.

1300
01:30:03.690 --> 01:30:04.649
Yes, of course.

1301
01:30:04.691 --> 01:30:05.901
And Aries,

1302
01:30:05.942 --> 01:30:07.194
god of war,
who blankets his bed

1303
01:30:07.236 --> 01:30:08.486
with the skin
of men he's killed?

1304
01:30:10.989 --> 01:30:14.492
All the gods are to be feared
and respected.

1305
01:30:25.337 --> 01:30:27.256
I'll tell you a secret--

1306
01:30:27.297 --> 01:30:31.093
something they don't teach you
in your temple.

1307
01:30:40.476 --> 01:30:44.189
The gods envy us.

1308
01:30:44.231 --> 01:30:46.858
They envy us
because we're mortal.

1309
01:30:48.360 --> 01:30:51.238
Because any moment
might be our last.

1310
01:30:51.280 --> 01:30:54.824
Everything's more beautiful
because we're doomed.

1311
01:30:56.076 --> 01:30:59.662
You will never be lovelier
than you are now.

1312
01:31:02.999 --> 01:31:05.043
We will never be here again.

1313
01:31:14.177 --> 01:31:16.388
I thought you were a dumb brute.

1314
01:31:19.557 --> 01:31:22.769
I could have forgiven
a dumb brute.

1315
01:31:43.957 --> 01:31:46.001
Do it.

1316
01:31:51.756 --> 01:31:53.716
Nothing is easier.

1317
01:31:53.758 --> 01:31:55.135
Aren't you afraid?

1318
01:31:56.970 --> 01:31:59.306
Everyone dies.

1319
01:31:59.348 --> 01:32:02.017
Today or 50 years from now,
what does it matter?

1320
01:32:06.313 --> 01:32:07.189
Do it.

1321
01:32:09.774 --> 01:32:12.319
You'll kill more men
if I don't kill you.

1322
01:32:12.361 --> 01:32:15.280
Many.

1323
01:32:38.011 --> 01:32:40.680
( knife clatters to ground )

1324
01:32:50.606 --> 01:32:53.693
♪ ♪

1325
01:33:04.371 --> 01:33:07.707
( waves crashing )

1326
01:33:27.727 --> 01:33:29.104
My lord, there's...

1327
01:33:44.244 --> 01:33:46.329
Tell the men to start
loading the ship.

1328
01:33:46.371 --> 01:33:47.997
We're going home.

1329
01:33:51.543 --> 01:33:52.961
Gather
the stores.

1330
01:33:53.002 --> 01:33:55.255
Prepare
the ship.

1331
01:33:58.883 --> 01:34:01.261
Agamemnon
is a proud man,

1332
01:34:01.303 --> 01:34:04.556
but he knows when
he's made a mistake.

1333
01:34:04.598 --> 01:34:07.100
The man sends you
to make his apologies?

1334
01:34:09.060 --> 01:34:11.938
What are you doing enthralled
to that pig of a king?

1335
01:34:11.980 --> 01:34:14.774
The world seems simple
to you, my friend,

1336
01:34:14.816 --> 01:34:16.359
but when you're a king,

1337
01:34:16.401 --> 01:34:18.320
very few choices
are simple.

1338
01:34:20.947 --> 01:34:23.908
Ithaca cannot afford
an enemy like Agamemnon.

1339
01:34:23.950 --> 01:34:25.701
Are we supposed
to fear him?

1340
01:34:25.743 --> 01:34:27.870
You don't fear anyone,
that's your problem.

1341
01:34:27.912 --> 01:34:30.123
Fear is useful.

1342
01:34:33.793 --> 01:34:35.295
We need you back.

1343
01:34:35.337 --> 01:34:37.130
Greece
needs you.

1344
01:34:37.172 --> 01:34:40.091
Greece got along fine
before I was born,

1345
01:34:40.133 --> 01:34:43.386
and Greece will be Greece
long after I'm dead.

1346
01:34:43.428 --> 01:34:44.678
I'm not talking
about the land.

1347
01:34:44.720 --> 01:34:47.432
The men need you.

1348
01:34:50.726 --> 01:34:52.854
Stay, Achilles.

1349
01:34:52.895 --> 01:34:55.565
You were born for this war.

1350
01:34:59.402 --> 01:35:01.237
Things are less simple today.

1351
01:35:03.114 --> 01:35:06.368
Women have a way
of complicating things.

1352
01:35:09.745 --> 01:35:11.289
( chuckles )

1353
01:35:11.331 --> 01:35:13.958
Of all the kings of Greece,
I respect you the most,

1354
01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:16.294
but in this war,
you're a servant.

1355
01:35:16.336 --> 01:35:19.922
Sometimes you have to serve
in order to lead.

1356
01:35:19.964 --> 01:35:22.925
I hope you understand
that one day.

1357
01:35:28.515 --> 01:35:30.684
We're going home?

1358
01:35:33.769 --> 01:35:35.146
We sail in the morning.

1359
01:35:35.188 --> 01:35:37.106
Greeks are being slaughtered.

1360
01:35:37.148 --> 01:35:38.816
We can't just sail away.

1361
01:35:38.858 --> 01:35:40.443
If it's fighting
you still long for,

1362
01:35:40.485 --> 01:35:41.861
there'll always be
another war.

1363
01:35:41.903 --> 01:35:42.862
That I promise you.

1364
01:35:42.904 --> 01:35:44.364
These are our countrymen.

